{"title_page": "Pulse Polio", "text_new": "[[File:Pulse Polio Day, Gwalior, January 2014.jpg|thumb|A child is vaccinated on Pulse Polio Day in Gwalior.]]\n'''Pulse Polio''' is an   [[immunisation]] campaign established by the [[government of India]] to eliminate   [[poliomyelitis]] (polio) in [[India]] by  vaccinating all children under the age of five years against the  [[poliomyelitis|polio virus]]. The project fights polio through a large-scale,  [[pulse vaccination]]  programme and monitoring for poliomyelitis cases. [[Vellore]] ,(Tamil Nadu) was the first Indian town to become 100% polio-free through the pulse strategy, and rest of India adopted the strategy in 1995.\n\n==History==\n\nIndia, vaccination against polio started on 1978 with Expanded Programme on Immunization (EPI). By 1999, it covered around 60% of infants, giving three doses of OPV to each.\n\nIn 1985,the Universal Immunization Programme  (UIP) was launched to cover all the districts of the country. UIP became a part of child survival and safe motherhood program (CSSM) in 1992 and Reproductive and Child Health Program (RCH) in 1997\n. This program led to a significant increase in coverage, up to 5%. The number of reported cases of polio also declined from thousands <!-- Correct number needed -->during 1987 to 42 in 2010.\n\nIn 1995, following the Global Polio Eradication Initiative of the World Health Organization (1988), India launched Pulse Polio immunization program with Universal Immunization Program which aimed at 100% coverage.\n\nThe last reported cases of wild polio in India were in West Bengal and Gujarat on 13 January 2011.<ref>{{cite web |title=Polio Global Eradication Initiative |url=http://www.polioeradication.org/InfectedCountries/India.aspx}}</ref> On 27 March 2014, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) declared India a polio free country, since no cases of wild polio been reported in for five years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/health/policy-and-issues/who-certifies-india-poliofree/article5839833.ece|title= WHO certifies India polio-free|date=27 March 2014|work=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref>\n\n==Preventive Pulse Polio==\n\nThe Pulse Polio Initiative (PPI) aims at covering every individual in the country. It aspires to reach even children in remote communities through an improved social mobilisation plan.<ref name=\"indiagovernance\">[http://indiagovernance.gov.in/bestpractices.php?id=143 Best Practices]</ref>\n\n* Not a single child should miss the immunization and leaving no chance of polio occurrence.\n* Cases of acute flaccid paralysis (AFP) to be reported in time and stool specimens of them to be collected within 14 days. Outbreak response immunisation (ORI) to be conducted as early as possible.\n* Maintaining a high level of surveillance.\n* Performance of good mop-up operations where polio has disappeared.<ref name=\"indiagovernance\"/>\n\n==Steps involved==\n\n* Setting up of booths in all parts of the country.<ref name=\"indiagovernance\"/>\n* Initialising walk-in cold rooms, freezer rooms, deep freezers, ice-lined refrigerators and cold boxes for a steady supply of vaccine to booths.\n* Arranging employees, volunteers, and vaccines.\n* Ensuring [[vaccine vial monitor]] on each vaccine [[vial]].\n* Immunising children with OPV on national immunisation days.\n* Identifying missing children from immunisation process.\n* Surveillance of efficacy.\n\nPublicity was extensive and included replacing the national telecoms' authority ringtone with a vaccination day awareness message, posters, TV and cinema spots, parades, rallies, and one-to-one communication from volunteers. Vaccination booths were set up, with a house-to-house campaign for remote communities.<ref name=rosa>{{cite web|title=Immunization Program|url=http://www.unicef.org/rosa/critical.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Difficulties==\n\nTesting showed that three doses of vaccine was enough to protect children in developed countries, but it became obvious that this was not enough in some areas of India. The Ministry of Health and Family Welfare recommended eight to ten doses for each child.\n\nChildren in some areas of India are weaker and often had diarrhea, which reduced the efficiency of the vaccine. [[Open defecation]], monsoon flooding, and a lack of water treatment made it easier for a child to swallow more polio virus. As a result, children with too few doses of vaccine were not fully protected and sometimes got polio.<ref name=rosa/>\n\nThe eradication program therefore gave drops over and over again, to boost children's immunity higher and as a precaution against missed children. Few parents initially knew that the vaccination campaign was trying to eradicate the disease, so they did not understand the reasons for the increasing intensity of vaccination. The increasing frequency of the drops and cases of polio among partially vaccinated children, caused rumours that the drops did not work.<ref name=rosa/>\n\nOn July 30, 2013 a nine-month-old boy from Navi Mumbai tested positive for vaccine-derived poliovirus (VDPV) type 2. This was the fourth such case recorded in the country in 2013.<ref name=hindu>{{cite news|title=Mumbai child becomes fourth Indian to get polio from vaccine|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/mumbai-child-becomes-fourth-indian-to-get-polio-from-vaccine/article4967388.ece|accessdate=2 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\nMany parts of India are remote and hard to access. People in some areas had had poor and caste-discriminatory treatment by government health authorities, which made them less willing to assist in the vaccination programme. The time demands of polio vaccination sometimes left health care workers with less time for other services. The absence of any free health services other than polio vaccination and contraception lead to rumours that the drops caused infertility.<ref name=rosa/>\n\nRumours about vaccinations varied by area, but were clustered, so that there was a greater risk of a cluster of unvaccinated children. Some believed that vaccinating newborns, children who are ill, or previously vaccinated children was not safe;<ref name=rosa/> the last polio case in India was a girl who had not been vaccinated because she was sickly.<ref name=\"edition.cnn.com\">http://edition.cnn.com/2014/03/22/health/india-end-of-polio/index.html</ref> There were also rumours that the polio drops were made from the blood of pigs, dogs, or mice, or from pig fat.<ref>{{cite web|title=Research Article|url=http://www.indianpediatrics.net/nov2009/963.pdf}}</ref>\n\nPoor participation of doctors and nurses, difficulty in maintaining and procuring vaccine, difficulty in procuring vehicles, and a lack of support from community members have caused problems in the program,<ref>{{cite web|title=Polio|url=http://health.bih.nic.in/PPProg.htm}}</ref> as has fatigue at the length of the anti-polio campaign.<ref name=rosa/>\n\n==Support==\nThe campaign was supported by organisations including the Indian federal and state governments, international institutions, and non-governmental organisations. It is part of the Global Polio Eradication Initiative, spearheaded by [[Rotary International]], the World Health Organization, [[UNICEF]], and the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.\n\nActor [[Amitabh Bachchan]] volunteered with the campaign, filming TV and radio spots urging against complacency<ref name=rosa/><ref>http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Amitabh-Bachchan-happy-with-polio-eradication-from-India/articleshow/38745401.cms</ref> and personally vaccinating children.<ref>http://unicef.in/PressReleases/69/Amitabh-Bachchan-launches-new-Polio-Communication-Campaign</ref>\n\nThe Indian and Afghan cricket teams have supported their national and international polio eradication efforts.<ref>http://www.unicef.org/infobycountry/india_53598.html</ref>\n\n==Correlation between non-polio acute flaccid paralysis rates with pulse polio frequency in India==\nA study observing data till the end of 2017 correlates non-polio acute flaccid paralysis rates with pulse polio frequency in India. The number of children in the world now paralyzed by mutant strains of the polio vaccine are greater than the number of children paralyzed by polio. WHO is attempting to phase out the use of live oral polio vaccine to eliminate the risk that the active virus in the vaccine could mutate into a form that can harm unvaccinated children.\n<ref>https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/30111741</ref><ref>https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2017/06/28/534403083/mutant-strains-of-polio-vaccine-now-cause-more-paralysis-than-wild-polio</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Polio]]\n* [[Eradication of polio]]\n* [[Healthcare in India]]\n* [[Vaccination]]\n* [[Polio Vaccine]]\n* [[Pulse vaccination strategy]]\n* ''[[Polio v/s Polio victims]]'', documentary about the campaign\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.pulsepolio.com/pulse-polio-immunization.htm Pulse Polio]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080423081712/http://onlypunjab.com/fullstory2k5-insight--status-22-newsID-25278.html India vaccinates nearly 80 million children]\n* [http://indiagovernance.gov.in/bestpractices.php?id=143 Indian Governance]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111125123317/http://www.iegindia.org/workpap/wp283.pdf IUEPN: India Unite to End Polio Now]\n{{Eradication of infectious disease}}\n\n[[Category:Health programmes in India]]\n[[Category:Polio]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Pulse Polio Day, Gwalior, January 2014.jpg|thumb|A child is vaccinated on Pulse Polio Day in Gwalior.]]\n'''Pulse Polio''' is an   [[immunisation]] campaign established by the [[government of India]] to eliminate   [[poliomyelitis]] (polio) in [[India]] by  vaccinating all children under the age of five years against the  [[poliomyelitis|polio virus]]. The project fights polio through a large-scale,  [[pulse vaccination]]  programme and monitoring for poliomyelitis cases. [[Vellore]] ,(Tamil Nadu) was the first Indian town to become 100% polio-free through the pulse strategy, and rest of India adopted the strategy in 1995.\n\n==History==\n\n  India, vaccination against polio started on 1978 with Expanded Programme on Immunization (EPI). By 1999, it covered around 60% of infants, giving three doses of OPV to each.\n\nIn 1985,the Universal Immunization Programme  (UIP) was launched to cover all the districts of the country. UIP became a part of child survival and safe motherhood program (CSSM) in 1992 and Reproductive and Child Health Program (RCH) in 1997\n. This program led to a significant increase in coverage, up to 5%. The number of reported cases of polio also declined from thousands <!-- Correct number needed -->during 1987 to 42 in 2010.\n\nIn 1995, following the Global Polio Eradication Initiative of the World Health Organization (1988), India launched Pulse Polio immunization program with Universal Immunization Program which aimed at 100% coverage.\n\nThe last reported cases of wild polio in India were in West Bengal and Gujarat on 13 January 2011.<ref>{{cite web |title=Polio Global Eradication Initiative |url=http://www.polioeradication.org/InfectedCountries/India.aspx}}</ref> On 27 March 2014, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) declared India a polio free country, since no cases of wild polio been reported in for five years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/health/policy-and-issues/who-certifies-india-poliofree/article5839833.ece|title= WHO certifies India polio-free|date=27 March 2014|work=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref>\n\n==Preventive Pulse Polio==\n\nThe Pulse Polio Initiative (PPI) aims at covering every individual in the country. It aspires to reach even children in remote communities through an improved social mobilisation plan.<ref name=\"indiagovernance\">[http://indiagovernance.gov.in/bestpractices.php?id=143 Best Practices]</ref>\n\n* Not a single child should miss the immunization and leaving no chance of polio occurrence.\n* Cases of acute flaccid paralysis (AFP) to be reported in time and stool specimens of them to be collected within 14 days. Outbreak response immunisation (ORI) to be conducted as early as possible.\n* Maintaining a high level of surveillance.\n* Performance of good mop-up operations where polio has disappeared.<ref name=\"indiagovernance\"/>\n\n==Steps involved==\n\n* Setting up of booths in all parts of the country.<ref name=\"indiagovernance\"/>\n* Initialising walk-in cold rooms, freezer rooms, deep freezers, ice-lined refrigerators and cold boxes for a steady supply of vaccine to booths.\n* Arranging employees, volunteers, and vaccines.\n* Ensuring [[vaccine vial monitor]] on each vaccine [[vial]].\n* Immunising children with OPV on national immunisation days.\n* Identifying missing children from immunisation process.\n* Surveillance of efficacy.\n\nPublicity was extensive and included replacing the national telecoms' authority ringtone with a vaccination day awareness message, posters, TV and cinema spots, parades, rallies, and one-to-one communication from volunteers. Vaccination booths were set up, with a house-to-house campaign for remote communities.<ref name=rosa>{{cite web|title=Immunization Program|url=http://www.unicef.org/rosa/critical.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Difficulties==\n\nTesting showed that three doses of vaccine was enough to protect children in developed countries, but it became obvious that this was not enough in some areas of India. The Ministry of Health and Family Welfare recommended eight to ten doses for each child.\n\nChildren in some areas of India are weaker and often had diarrhea, which reduced the efficiency of the vaccine. [[Open defecation]], monsoon flooding, and a lack of water treatment made it easier for a child to swallow more polio virus. As a result, children with too few doses of vaccine were not fully protected and sometimes got polio.<ref name=rosa/>\n\nThe eradication program therefore gave drops over and over again, to boost children's immunity higher and as a precaution against missed children. Few parents initially knew that the vaccination campaign was trying to eradicate the disease, so they did not understand the reasons for the increasing intensity of vaccination. The increasing frequency of the drops and cases of polio among partially vaccinated children, caused rumours that the drops did not work.<ref name=rosa/>\n\nOn July 30, 2013 a nine-month-old boy from Navi Mumbai tested positive for vaccine-derived poliovirus (VDPV) type 2. This was the fourth such case recorded in the country in 2013.<ref name=hindu>{{cite news|title=Mumbai child becomes fourth Indian to get polio from vaccine|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/mumbai-child-becomes-fourth-indian-to-get-polio-from-vaccine/article4967388.ece|accessdate=2 January 2015|publisher=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\nMany parts of India are remote and hard to access. People in some areas had had poor and caste-discriminatory treatment by government health authorities, which made them less willing to assist in the vaccination programme. The time demands of polio vaccination sometimes left health care workers with less time for other services. The absence of any free health services other than polio vaccination and contraception lead to rumours that the drops caused infertility.<ref name=rosa/>\n\nRumours about vaccinations varied by area, but were clustered, so that there was a greater risk of a cluster of unvaccinated children. Some believed that vaccinating newborns, children who are ill, or previously vaccinated children was not safe;<ref name=rosa/> the last polio case in India was a girl who had not been vaccinated because she was sickly.<ref name=\"edition.cnn.com\">http://edition.cnn.com/2014/03/22/health/india-end-of-polio/index.html</ref> There were also rumours that the polio drops were made from the blood of pigs, dogs, or mice, or from pig fat.<ref>{{cite web|title=Research Article|url=http://www.indianpediatrics.net/nov2009/963.pdf}}</ref>\n\nPoor participation of doctors and nurses, difficulty in maintaining and procuring vaccine, difficulty in procuring vehicles, and a lack of support from community members have caused problems in the program,<ref>{{cite web|title=Polio|url=http://health.bih.nic.in/PPProg.htm}}</ref> as has fatigue at the length of the anti-polio campaign.<ref name=rosa/>\n\n==Support==\nThe campaign was supported by organisations including the Indian federal and state governments, international institutions, and non-governmental organisations. It is part of the Global Polio Eradication Initiative, spearheaded by [[Rotary International]], the World Health Organization, [[UNICEF]], and the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.\n\nActor [[Amitabh Bachchan]] volunteered with the campaign, filming TV and radio spots urging against complacency<ref name=rosa/><ref>http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Amitabh-Bachchan-happy-with-polio-eradication-from-India/articleshow/38745401.cms</ref> and personally vaccinating children.<ref>http://unicef.in/PressReleases/69/Amitabh-Bachchan-launches-new-Polio-Communication-Campaign</ref>\n\nThe Indian and Afghan cricket teams have supported their national and international polio eradication efforts.<ref>http://www.unicef.org/infobycountry/india_53598.html</ref>\n\n==Correlation between non-polio acute flaccid paralysis rates with pulse polio frequency in India==\nA study observing data till the end of 2017 correlates non-polio acute flaccid paralysis rates with pulse polio frequency in India. The number of children in the world now paralyzed by mutant strains of the polio vaccine are greater than the number of children paralyzed by polio. WHO is attempting to phase out the use of live oral polio vaccine to eliminate the risk that the active virus in the vaccine could mutate into a form that can harm unvaccinated children.\n<ref>https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/30111741</ref><ref>https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2017/06/28/534403083/mutant-strains-of-polio-vaccine-now-cause-more-paralysis-than-wild-polio</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Polio]]\n* [[Eradication of polio]]\n* [[Healthcare in India]]\n* [[Vaccination]]\n* [[Polio Vaccine]]\n* [[Pulse vaccination strategy]]\n* ''[[Polio v/s Polio victims]]'', documentary about the campaign\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.pulsepolio.com/pulse-polio-immunization.htm Pulse Polio]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080423081712/http://onlypunjab.com/fullstory2k5-insight--status-22-newsID-25278.html India vaccinates nearly 80 million children]\n* [http://indiagovernance.gov.in/bestpractices.php?id=143 Indian Governance]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111125123317/http://www.iegindia.org/workpap/wp283.pdf IUEPN: India Unite to End Polio Now]\n{{Eradication of infectious disease}}\n\n[[Category:Health programmes in India]]\n[[Category:Polio]]\n", "name_user": "Akhilan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pulse_Polio"}
{"title_page": "Shaktikanta Das", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Shaktikanta Das\n| office5             = [[Secretary to the Government of India|Fertilizers Secretary]]\n| predecessor         = [[Urjit Patel]]\n| president           = [[Ram Nath Kovind]]\n| primeminister       = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| Minister            = \n| office              = 25th{{nbsp}}[[List of Governors of Reserve Bank of India|Governor of the Reserve Bank of India]]\n| native_name         = \n| image               = File:Shaktikanta Das, IAS.jpg\n| caption             = \n| successor           = \n| termend             = \n| termstart           = {{Date|2018-12-12|df=dmy}}\n| alongside2          = [[Ashok Lahiri]]<br />[[Anoop Chand]]<br />[[Ramesh Chand]]\n| appointer2          = [[President of India]] {{small|(then, [[Ramnath Kovind]])}}\n| appointer1          = [[Appointments Committee of the Cabinet]]\n| governor1           = [[Urjit Patel]]\n| minister1           = [[Arun Jaitley]]\n| office1             = [[Sherpa (emissary)|Sherpa]] of India to the [[G20]]\n| predecessor1        = [[Arvind Panagariya]]\n| primeminister1      = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| successor1          = \n| termstart1          = {{Date|2017-11-27|df=dmy}}\n| termend1            = {{Date|2018-12-11|df=dmy}}\n| office3             = [[Economic Affairs Secretary]]\n| predecessor3        = [[Rajiv Mehrishi]]\n| successor3          = [[Subhash Chandra Garg]]\n| predecessor4        = [[Rajiv Thakur]]\n| office2             = [[Fifteenth Finance Commission#Members|Member of the Fifteenth{{nbsp}}Finance Commission]]\n| predecessor2        = \n| successor2          = [[Ajay Narayan Jha]]\n| termend2            = {{Date|2018-12-11|df=dmy}}\n| office4             = [[Revenue Secretary]]\n| termstart2          = {{Date|2017-11-27|df=dmy}}\n| termend3            = {{Date|2017-05-28|df=dmy}}\n| termstart3          = {{Date|2015-08-31|df=dmy}}\n| termend4            = {{Date|2015-08-31|df=dmy}}\n| termstart4          = {{Date|2014-06-16|df=dmy}}\n| successor4          = [[Hasmukh Adhia]]\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1957|02|26|df=z}}\n| birth_place         = [[Bhubaneswar]], Orissa, India<br />{{small|(now, Bhubaneswar, [[Odisha]], India)}}\n| occupation          = Retired [[Indian Administrative Service|IAS]] officer\n| 2blankname2         = Chairman\n| 2namedata2          = [[N. K. Singh]]\n| termstart5          = {{Date||2013-12-30|df=dmy}}\n| termend5            = {{Date||2014-06-15|df=dmy}}\n| appointer3          = [[Appointments Committee of the Cabinet]]\n| appointer4          = [[Appointments Committee of the Cabinet]]\n| appointer5          = [[Appointments Committee of the Cabinet]]\n| minister3           = [[Arun Jaitley]]\n| minister4           = [[Arun Jaitley]]\n| alma_mater          = [[University of Delhi]] {{small|([[B.A.|BA]], [[M.A.|MA]])}}\n| profession          = [[Civil service|Civil servant]]\n}}\n'''Shaktikanta Das''' (born {{Date|1957-02-26|dmy}}) Brahmin family\n is a retired 1980{{Nbsp}}batch [[Indian Administrative Service]] (IAS) officer of [[Tamil Nadu]] cadre. Currently serving as the 25th [[List of Governors of Reserve Bank of India|governor]] of the [[Reserve Bank of India]] (RBI), he was earlier a member of the [[Fifteenth Finance Commission|Fifteenth{{Nbsp}}Finance Commission]] and India's [[Sherpa (emissary)|Sherpa]] to the [[G20]].\n\nDuring his career as an IAS officer, Das served in various capacities for [[Government of India|Indian]] and [[Government of Tamil Nadu|Tamil Nadu]] governments, including as [[Economic Affairs Secretary]], [[Revenue Secretary]], [[Secretary to the Government of India|Fertilizers Secretary]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nBorn in [[Bhubaneswar]],<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/shaktikanta-das-a-budget-veteran-comes-to-mint-street/articleshow/67054166.cms|title=Shaktikanta Das: A budget veteran comes to Mint Street|last=Siddharta|last2=Gupta|first2=Surojit|date=12 December 2018|website=[[The Times of India]]|publisher=[[Bennett, Coleman & Co. Ltd.]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|oclc=23379369|access-date=12 December 2018}}</ref> Das was schooled at the [[Demonstration Multipurpose School, Bhubaneswar]],<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=846044393790357504|user=dpradhanbjp|title=Attended the alumni function of DM school, BBSR. Felicitated Sh @DasShaktikanta, Secretary Govt of India & a proud alumni of the school.|author=Dharmendra Pradhan|author-link=Dharmendra Pradhan|date=26 March 2017|access-date=12 December 2018}}</ref> and then obtained [[Bachelor's degree|bachelor's]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]]) and [[Master's degree|master's]] degrees ([[Master of Arts|MA]]) in [[history]] from the [[St. Stephen's College, Delhi|St. Stephen's College]] at the [[University of Delhi]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://supremo.nic.in/ERSheetHtml.aspx?OffIDErhtml=14205&PageId=|title=Shaktikanta Das \u2013 Executive Record Sheet|website=Department of Personnel and Training, [[Ministry of Personnel, Public Grievances and Pensions]], [[Government of India]]|access-date=16 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== As an IAS officer ===\nDas served in various positions for both the [[Government of India]] and the [[Government of Tamil Nadu]], like as [[Principal secretary (India)|Principal Secretary]] ([[Department of Industries (Tamil Nadu)|Industries]]), Special Commissioner ([[Department of Revenue (Tamil Nadu)|Revenue]]), Secretary (Revenue), Secretary ([[Department of Commercial Taxes (Tamil Nadu)|Commercial Taxes]]), the project director of [[Tamil Nadu State AIDS Control Society]] and as the [[District collector (India)|district magistrate and collector]] of [[Dindigul district|Dindigul]] and [[Kanchipuram district|Kancheepuram]] [[List of districts in Tamil Nadu|districts]] in the [[Government of Tamil Nadu|Tamil Nadu government]];<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> and as [[Economic Affairs Secretary|Union Economic Affairs Secretary]], [[Revenue Secretary|Union Revenue Secretary]], [[Secretary to the Government of India|Union Fertilizers Secretary]], [[Special secretary to the Government of India|special secretary]] in the [[Department of Economic Affairs (India)|Department of Economic Affairs]] of the [[Ministry of Finance (India)|Ministry of Finance]] and as a [[Joint secretary to the Government of India|joint secretary]] in the [[Department of Expenditure]] of the [[Ministry of Finance (India)|Ministry of Finance]] in the [[Government of India|Indian government]].<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDas also had a stint with Mahindra Industrial Park Ltd ([[Mahindra World City, New Chennai|Mahindra World City]]), on deputation to a [[Private sector|private sector company]] under Rule{{Nbsp}}6(2)(ii) of the Indian Administrative Service (Cadre) Rules, 1954.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dopt.gov.in/sites/default/files/Revised_AIS_Rule_Vol_II_IAS_Rule_01_0.pdf|title=The Indian Administrative Service (Cadre) rules, 1954|last=|first=|date=1954|website=Department of Personnel and Training, [[Government of India]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=13 August 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Shaktikanta Das, IAS signing FATCA.jpg|left|thumb|Das (left) with the [[List of ambassadors of the United States to India|United States ambassador to India]] [[Richard Verma]] (right) on the signing of [[Foreign Account Tax Compliance Act|FATCA]] in [[New Delhi]] on {{date|July 9, 2015|dmy}}|alt=]]\n\n==== Revenue Secretary ====\nDas was appointed [[Revenue Secretary|Union Revenue Secretary]] by the [[Prime Minister of India|prime minister]]-led-[[Appointments Committee of the Cabinet]] (ACC) in {{Date|June 2014|dmy}},<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/shaktikanta-das-appointed-as-revenue-secretary-114061600671_1.html|title=Shaktikanta Das appointed as Revenue Secretary|last=|first=|date=June 16, 2014|website=[[Business Standard]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/shaktikanta-das-appointed-as-revenue-secretary/article6114678.ece|title=Shaktikanta Das appointed as Revenue Secretary|last=Sinha|first=Shishir|date=June 14, 2014|website=[[Business Line]]|publisher=[[The Hindu Group]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|issn=0971-7528|oclc=456162874|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/3O8NDeauXw5oKei9PnStpM/Shaktikanta-Das-takes-charge-as-revenue-secretary.html|title=Shaktikanta Das takes charge as revenue secretary|last=|first=|date=June 16, 2014|website=Livemint|publisher=[[HT Media Ltd]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref> he assumed the office of Secretary on {{Date|2014-06-16|dmy}},<ref name=\":0\" /> and demitted it on {{Date|2015-08-31|dmy}}.<ref name=\":0\" />\n[[File:Arun Jaitley, the Secretary, Department of Economic Affairs, Shri Shaktikanta Das and the President, CII, Shri Naushad Forbes.jpg|thumb|Das (right) with [[Minister of Finance (India)|Minister of Finance]] [[Arun Jaitley]] (centre) and the president of [[Confederation of Indian Industry]] [[Naushad Forbes]] (left)]]\n\n==== Economic Affairs Secretary ====\nDas was appointed [[Economic Affairs Secretary|Union Economic Affairs Secretary]] by the ACC in {{Date|August 2014|dmy}},<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/shaktikanta-das-appointed-economic-affairs-secretary-hasmukh-adhia-is-new-revenue-secretary/articleshow/48715974.cms|title=Shaktikanta Das appointed Economic Affairs Secretary; Hasmukh Adhia is new Revenue Secretary|last=|first=|date=August 29, 2015|website=[[The Economic Times]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/das-is-new-economic-affairs-secy-hasmukh-adhia-revenue-secretary/|title=Das is new economic affairs secy, Hasmukh Adhia revenue secretary|date=August 29, 2015|website=[[The Indian Express]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|oclc=70274541|access-date=January 15, 2018|agency=Express News Service}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/shaktikanta-das-takes-charge-as-economic-affairs-secretary-1213313|title=Shaktikanta Das Takes Charge as Economic Affairs Secretary|last=|first=|date=September 2, 2015|website=[[NDTV]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref> he assumed the office of Secretary on {{Date|2015-08-31|dmy}},<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> and admitted it and simultaneously [[Pension|superannuated]] from service on {{Date|2017-05-28|dmy}},<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> after being given a three-month{{Nbsp}}extension by the government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/business/DEA-Secretary-Shaktikanta-Das-gets-3-month-extension/article17083022.ece|title=DEA Secretary Shaktikanta Das gets 3-month extension|last=|first=|date=January 23, 2017|website=[[The Hindu]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/dea-secretary-shaktikanta-das-gets-3-month-extension-117012301178_1.html|title=DEA Secretary Shaktikanta Das gets 3-month extension|last=|first=|date=January 23, 2017|website=[[Business Standard]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/govt-extends-economic-affairs-secretary-shaktikanta-das-tenure-by-3-months/articleshow/56738856.cms|title=Govt extends Economic Affairs Secretary Shaktikanta Das' tenure by 3 months|last=|first=|date=January 24, 2017|website=[[The Economic Times]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring his tenure as [[Secretary to Government of India|Union Economic Affairs Secretary]], Das was widely regarded as one of the most powerful civil servants in India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/modi-government-bureaucrats-ajit-doval-nripendra-misra-s-jaishankar/1/927889.html|title=The game changers|last=Unnithan|first=Sandeep|date=April 13, 2017|website=[[India Today]]|issn=0254-8399|access-date=11 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/the-crack-team-those-who-made-gst-a-reality/shaktikanta-das-former-revenue-and-economic-affairs-secretary/slideshow/59400919.cms|title=The crack team: Those who made GST a reality - Shaktikanta Das, Former Revenue and Economic Affairs Secretary|date=1 July 2017|website=[[The Economic Times]]|publisher=[[The Times Group]]|oclc=61311680|access-date=11 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Post retirement ===\nPost his retirement from the IAS, Das was appointed a member of the [[Fifteenth Finance Commission|Fifteenth{{Nbsp}}Finance Commission]] by the ACC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/n-k-singh-heads-15th-finance-commission-shaktikanta-das-a-member-117112701199_1.html|title=N.K. Singh heads 15th Finance Commission, Shaktikanta Das a member|last=|first=|date=November 27, 2017|website=[[Business Standard]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/nk-singh-appointed-chairman-of-15th-finance-commission/article9974029.ece|title=NK Singh appointed Chairman of 15th Finance Commission|last=|first=|date=November 27, 2017|website=Business Line|publisher=[[The Hindu]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/rWfJyCZBIkttQMKHXoZBHO/NK-Singh-appointed-chairman-of-15th-Finance-Commission.html|title=N.K. Singh appointed chairman of 15th Finance Commission|last=|first=|date=November 27, 2017|website=Livemint|publisher=[[HT Media Ltd]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/former-planning-commission-member-nk-singh-appointed-15th-finance-commission-chairman-1780855|title=Former Planning Commission Member NK Singh Appointed 15th Finance Commission Chairman|last=|first=|date=November 28, 2017|website=[[NDTV]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref> In addition, he was appointed as India's [[Sherpa (emissary)|Sherpa]] to the [[G20]] by the ACC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/former-dea-secretary-shaktikanta-das-confirmed-as-g-20-sherpa-117112800060_1.html|title=Former DEA secretary Shaktikanta Das confirmed as G-20 sherpa|last=|first=|date=November 28, 2017|website=[[Business Standard]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/shaktikanta-das-appointed-indias-g20-sherpa-until-december-31-2018/949913/|title=Shaktikanta Das appointed India\u2019s G20 Sherpa until December 31, 2018|date=November 27, 2017|website=[[The Financial Express (India)|The Financial Express]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/shaktikanta-das-appointed-as-indias-g20-sherpa/articleshow/61823581.cms|title=Shaktikanta Das appointed as India's G20 Sherpa. On 12th December, 2018, he has been appointed as the 25th Governor of the Reserve Bank of India for a period of three years.|last=|first=|date=November 27, 2017|website=[[The Times of India]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref> In {{Date|December 2018|dmy}}, on his appointment as the governor of the Reserve Bank of India, Das resigned from his position in the Fifteenth{{Nbsp}}Finance Commission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dea.gov.in/sites/default/files/Acceptance%20of%20resignation%20of%20Shri%20Shaktikanta%20Das-Member,%20FFC-11-12-2018.PDF|title=Acceptance of resignation of Shri Shaktikanta Das-Member, FFC|date=11 December 2018|website=[[Department of Economic Affairs (India)|Department of Economic Affairs]], [[Ministry of Finance (India)|Ministry of Finance]], [[Government of India]]|access-date=16 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Governor of Reserve Bank of India ====\nDas was appointed [[List of Governors of Reserve Bank of India|Governor of the Reserve Bank of India]] by the ACC on {{Date|2018-12-11|dmy}} for a period of three{{Nbsp}}years, replacing [[Urjit Patel]] who had resigned the day before.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/Industry/mqqkVZgURWChvJbxq45E4H/Shaktikanta-Das-appointed-new-RBI-governor.html|title=Shaktikanta Das, who oversaw demonetization, is new RBI governor|last=Prasad|first=Gireesh Chandra|last2=Ghosh|first2=Shayan|date=11 December 2018|website=[[Livemint]]|publisher=Vivek Khanna|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]/[[Mumbai]]|access-date=12 December 2018|last3=Gopakumar|first3=Gopika}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/business/shaktikanta-das-is-new-rbi-governor|title=Shaktikanta Das Is New RBI Governor|date=11 December 2018|website=[[BloombergQuint]]|others=BQ Desk|access-date=11 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/banking/finance/banking/shaktikanta-das-the-man-behind-gst-note-ban-now-heads-rbi/articleshow/67046113.cms|title=Shaktikanta Das: The man behind GST, note ban now heads RBI|date=11 December 2018|work=[[The Economic Times]]|access-date=11 December 2018|publisher=[[The Times Group]]|others=ET Online|oclc=61311680}}</ref>\n\nDas' appointment as RBI governor received mostly positive responses,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/how-shaktikanta-das-may-aid-regain-overseas-investor-confidence/articleshow/67049476.cms|title=How Shaktikanta Das may aid regain overseas investor confidence|last=Das|first=Saikat|date=11 December 2018|work=[[The Economic Times]]|access-date=12 December 2018|publisher=[[The Times Group]]|publication-place=[[Mumbai]]|oclc=61311680}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://in.reuters.com/article/india-cenbank-governor-idINKBN1OA1N0|title=Expert Views: India appoints Shaktikanta Das as RBI governor|last=Kurup|first=Krishna V.|date=11 December 2018|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=12 December 2018|agency=[[Reuters]]|last2=Thomas|first2=Chris|editor-last=Miglani|editor-first=Sanjeev|publication-place=[[Bengaluru]]/[[New Delhi]]|last3=Monnappa|first3=Chandini|last4=Dasgupta|first4=Neha|editor2-first=Sai Sachin|editor2-last=Ravikumar}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/business/Economy/has-handled-all-his-assignments-well/article25720280.ece|title=\u2018Shaktikanta Das handled all his assignments well\u2019|date=11 December 2018|work=[[The Hindu]]|access-date=12 December 2018|publisher=[[N. Ram]]|others=Special Correspondent|publication-place=[[Chennai]]|issn=0971-751X|oclc=13119119}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/economy/mit-economist-abhijit-banerjee-flays-government-in-appointing-shaktikanta-das-as-rbi-governor/1411091/|title=MIT economist Abhijit Banerjee flays government in appointing Shaktikanta Das as RBI Governor|date=11 December 2018|website=[[The Financial Express (India)|The Financial Express]]|oclc=30000665|access-date=12 December 2018|agency=[[Press Trust of India]]}}</ref> with [[DBS Bank]]'s head of markets for India at Singapore, Ashish Vaidya, saying that previous governors of the RBI with an [[Indian Administrative Service|IAS]] background, such as [[Y. Venugopal Reddy]] and [[Duvvuri Subbarao]], had been successful and that Das' \"cordial relations with the government [...] [would] likely help policy negotiations.\"<ref name=\":2\" /> [[S. S. Mundra]], a former [[Deputy Governor of the Reserve Bank of India|deputy governor]] of the RBI, said Das was a \"good and balanced choice\" for RBI governorship and had \"a good understanding of the whole of the financial sector both from the ministry and also in his interactions with the RBI.\"<ref name=\":5\" />  A former [[Governor of the Reserve Bank of India]] [[C. Rangarajan]], said Das had \"experience in economic affairs\" and would \"make a good governor\".<ref name=\":6\" /> Gaurav Shah, a senior vice president at [[Geojit Financial Services]], said \"a name like Shaktikanta Das carries track record, experience, credentials, credibility and respect along with him.\"<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nOn the other hand, Nobel laureate and professor at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], [[Abhijit Banerjee]], said Das' appointment posed a lot of \"frightening\" questions on governance of autonomous public institutions.<ref name=\":3\" /> [[Subramanian Swamy]], a member of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]], the largest party of the ruling [[National Democratic Alliance (India)|National Democratic Alliance]] [[Coalition government|coalition]], and a nominated [[Member of parliament, Rajya Sabha|member of the Rajya Sabha]] (Council of the States), criticised Das, calling him a \"corrupt person\" at an event at the [[Indian School of Business]] in [[Hyderabad]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/rbi-governor-saktikanta-das-highly-corrupt-says-swamy/cid/1679687|title=RBI chief Saktikanta Das 'corrupt', says Swamy|date=23 December 2018|website=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]|publication-place=[[Hyderabad]]|oclc=271717941|access-date=24 December 2018|agency=[[Press Trust of India]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/latest/906736/subramanian-swamy-claims-new-rbi-governor-shaktikanta-das-is-a-corrupt-person|title=Subramanian Swamy claims new RBI governor Shaktikanta Das is a \u2018corrupt person\u2019|date=23 December 2018|website=[[Scroll.in]]|others=Scroll Staff|access-date=24 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nDas assumed charge as RBI governor on {{Date|2018-12-12|dmy}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/business/rbi-governor-shaktikanta-das-takes-charge-seen-as-a-safe-bet-by-govt-new-chief-of-mint-street-starts-on-a-weak-wicket-5715031.html|title=RBI governor Shaktikanta Das takes charge: Seen as a safe bet by govt, new chief of Mint Street starts on a weak wicket|last=Kaul|first=Vivek|date=12 December 2018|website=[[Firstpost]]|publisher=[[Network 18]]|access-date=12 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/shaktikanta-das-takes-charge-as-25th-governor-of-the-rbi/articleshow/67054312.cms|title=Shaktikanta Das takes charge as 25th Governor of the RBI|date=12 December 2018|work=[[The Economic Times]]|access-date=12 December 2018|publisher=[[The Times Group]]|others=ET Online|oclc=61311680}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/rbi-governor/shaktikanta-das-takes-charge-as-25th-rbi-governor|title=Shaktikanta Das Takes Charge As 25th RBI Governor|date=12 December 2018|website=[[BloombergQuint]]|others=BQ Desk|access-date=12 December 2018}}</ref> Reactions of the markets to Das' appointment was positive, with [[BSE SENSEX]] gaining 629{{Nbsp}}points and [[NIFTY 50]] increasing by 188{{Nbsp}}points.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/markets-end-higher-as-new-rbi-chief-takes-charge-sensex-surges-629-points/articleshow/67058356.cms|title=Markets end higher as new RBI chief takes charge, Sensex surges 629 points|date=12 December 2018|website=[[The Times of India]]|publisher=[[Bennett, Coleman & Co. Ltd.]]|others=TIMESOFINDIA.COM|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|oclc=23379369|access-date=12 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/Money/OOEBbhmz7RJAHSO8q5ceuO/Markets-LIVE-Sensex-Nifty-set-for-cautious-start.html|title=Closing bell: Sensex surges 629 points, Nifty above 10,700 after RBI chief appointment|date=12 December 2018|website=[[Mint (newspaper)|Livemint]]|publisher=Vivek Khanna|others=Livemint|publication-place=[[Mumbai]]|access-date=12 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/market/sensex-nifty-post-biggest-1-day-gain-in-5-weeks-here-are-3-key-reasons-behind-surge/1411869/|title=Sensex, Nifty post biggest 1-day gain in 5 weeks; here are 3 key reasons behind surge|date=12 December 2018|website=[[The Financial Express (India)|The Financial Express]]|others=FE Online|oclc=30000665|access-date=12 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lh1yWyFuLQI|title=Who is the new RBI Governor|date=December 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs RBI governor, Das serves as the ''ex-officio'' chairperson of the [[Monetary Policy Committee (India)|Monetary Policy Committee]] of the central bank.<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/newly-appointed-deputy-governor-to-look-after-rbi-s-monetary-policy-division-11579097609165.html|title=Newly appointed deputy governor to look after RBI's monetary policy division|date=2020-01-15|website=[[Livemint]]|publisher=Vivek Khanna|language=en|publication-place=[[Mumbai]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-16|agency=[[Press Trust of India]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/banking/finance/banking/rbi-appoints-ed-janak-raj-as-member-of-mpc/articleshow/73741480.cms|title=RBI appoints ED Janak Raj as member of MPC|date=2020-01-29|work=[[The Economic Times]]|access-date=2020-04-03|url-status=live|agency=[[Press Trust of India]]|publication-place=[[Mumbai]]|issn=0013-0389|oclc=61311680}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Shaktikanta Das}}\n*{{URL|1=https://supremo.nic.in/ERSheetHtml.aspx?OffIDErhtml=14205&PageId=|2=Executive record sheet, as maintained by the Department of Personnel and Training of the Ministry of Personnel, Public Grievances and Pensions of the Government of India}}\n*{{URL|1=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=27531155&privcapId=882940|2=Executive profile, as maintained by Bloomberg}}\n\n{{Governors of Reserve Bank of India}}\n{{G20-CBGovernors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Das, Shaktikanta}}\n[[Category:Indian Administrative Service officers]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Bhubaneswar]]\n[[Category:Governors of the Reserve Bank of India]]\n[[Category:Indian diplomats]]\n[[Category:St. Stephen's College, Delhi alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Shaktikanta Das\n| office5             = [[Secretary to the Government of India|Fertilizers Secretary]]\n| predecessor         = [[Urjit Patel]]\n| president           = [[Ram Nath Kovind]]\n| primeminister       = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| Minister            = \n| office              = 25th{{nbsp}}[[List of Governors of Reserve Bank of India|Governor of the Reserve Bank of India]]\n| native_name         = \n| image               = File:Shaktikanta Das, IAS.jpg\n| caption             = \n| successor           = \n| termend             = \n| termstart           = {{Date|2018-12-12|df=dmy}}\n| alongside2          = [[Ashok Lahiri]]<br />[[Anoop Chand]]<br />[[Ramesh Chand]]\n| appointer2          = [[