ley]]\n| alma_mater          = [[University of Delhi]] {{small|([[B.A.|BA]], [[M.A.|MA]])}}\n| profession          = [[Civil service|Civil servant]]\n}}\n'''Shaktikanta Das''' (born {{Date|1957-02-26|dmy}}) is a retired 1980{{Nbsp}}batch [[Indian Administrative Service]] (IAS) officer of [[Tamil Nadu]] cadre. Currently serving as the 25th [[List of Governors of Reserve Bank of India|governor]] of the [[Reserve Bank of India]] (RBI), he was earlier a member of the [[Fifteenth Finance Commission|Fifteenth{{Nbsp}}Finance Commission]] and India's [[Sherpa (emissary)|Sherpa]] to the [[G20]].\n\nDuring his career as an IAS officer, Das served in various capacities for [[Government of India|Indian]] and [[Government of Tamil Nadu|Tamil Nadu]] governments, including as [[Economic Affairs Secretary]], [[Revenue Secretary]], [[Secretary to the Government of India|Fertilizers Secretary]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nBorn in [[Bhubaneswar]],<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/shaktikanta-das-a-budget-veteran-comes-to-mint-street/articleshow/67054166.cms|title=Shaktikanta Das: A budget veteran comes to Mint Street|last=Siddharta|last2=Gupta|first2=Surojit|date=12 December 2018|website=[[The Times of India]]|publisher=[[Bennett, Coleman & Co. Ltd.]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|oclc=23379369|access-date=12 December 2018}}</ref> Das was schooled at the [[Demonstration Multipurpose School, Bhubaneswar]],<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=846044393790357504|user=dpradhanbjp|title=Attended the alumni function of DM school, BBSR. Felicitated Sh @DasShaktikanta, Secretary Govt of India & a proud alumni of the school.|author=Dharmendra Pradhan|author-link=Dharmendra Pradhan|date=26 March 2017|access-date=12 December 2018}}</ref> and then obtained [[Bachelor's degree|bachelor's]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]]) and [[Master's degree|master's]] degrees ([[Master of Arts|MA]]) in [[history]] from the [[St. Stephen's College, Delhi|St. Stephen's College]] at the [[University of Delhi]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://supremo.nic.in/ERSheetHtml.aspx?OffIDErhtml=14205&PageId=|title=Shaktikanta Das \u2013 Executive Record Sheet|website=Department of Personnel and Training, [[Ministry of Personnel, Public Grievances and Pensions]], [[Government of India]]|access-date=16 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== As an IAS officer ===\nDas served in various positions for both the [[Government of India]] and the [[Government of Tamil Nadu]], like as [[Principal secretary (India)|Principal Secretary]] ([[Department of Industries (Tamil Nadu)|Industries]]), Special Commissioner ([[Department of Revenue (Tamil Nadu)|Revenue]]), Secretary (Revenue), Secretary ([[Department of Commercial Taxes (Tamil Nadu)|Commercial Taxes]]), the project director of [[Tamil Nadu State AIDS Control Society]] and as the [[District collector (India)|district magistrate and collector]] of [[Dindigul district|Dindigul]] and [[Kanchipuram district|Kancheepuram]] [[List of districts in Tamil Nadu|districts]] in the [[Government of Tamil Nadu|Tamil Nadu government]];<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> and as [[Economic Affairs Secretary|Union Economic Affairs Secretary]], [[Revenue Secretary|Union Revenue Secretary]], [[Secretary to the Government of India|Union Fertilizers Secretary]], [[Special secretary to the Government of India|special secretary]] in the [[Department of Economic Affairs (India)|Department of Economic Affairs]] of the [[Ministry of Finance (India)|Ministry of Finance]] and as a [[Joint secretary to the Government of India|joint secretary]] in the [[Department of Expenditure]] of the [[Ministry of Finance (India)|Ministry of Finance]] in the [[Government of India|Indian government]].<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDas also had a stint with Mahindra Industrial Park Ltd ([[Mahindra World City, New Chennai|Mahindra World City]]), on deputation to a [[Private sector|private sector company]] under Rule{{Nbsp}}6(2)(ii) of the Indian Administrative Service (Cadre) Rules, 1954.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dopt.gov.in/sites/default/files/Revised_AIS_Rule_Vol_II_IAS_Rule_01_0.pdf|title=The Indian Administrative Service (Cadre) rules, 1954|last=|first=|date=1954|website=Department of Personnel and Training, [[Government of India]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=13 August 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Shaktikanta Das, IAS signing FATCA.jpg|left|thumb|Das (left) with the [[List of ambassadors of the United States to India|United States ambassador to India]] [[Richard Verma]] (right) on the signing of [[Foreign Account Tax Compliance Act|FATCA]] in [[New Delhi]] on {{date|July 9, 2015|dmy}}|alt=]]\n\n==== Revenue Secretary ====\nDas was appointed [[Revenue Secretary|Union Revenue Secretary]] by the [[Prime Minister of India|prime minister]]-led-[[Appointments Committee of the Cabinet]] (ACC) in {{Date|June 2014|dmy}},<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/shaktikanta-das-appointed-as-revenue-secretary-114061600671_1.html|title=Shaktikanta Das appointed as Revenue Secretary|last=|first=|date=June 16, 2014|website=[[Business Standard]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/shaktikanta-das-appointed-as-revenue-secretary/article6114678.ece|title=Shaktikanta Das appointed as Revenue Secretary|last=Sinha|first=Shishir|date=June 14, 2014|website=[[Business Line]]|publisher=[[The Hindu Group]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|issn=0971-7528|oclc=456162874|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/3O8NDeauXw5oKei9PnStpM/Shaktikanta-Das-takes-charge-as-revenue-secretary.html|title=Shaktikanta Das takes charge as revenue secretary|last=|first=|date=June 16, 2014|website=Livemint|publisher=[[HT Media Ltd]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref> he assumed the office of Secretary on {{Date|2014-06-16|dmy}},<ref name=\":0\" /> and demitted it on {{Date|2015-08-31|dmy}}.<ref name=\":0\" />\n[[File:Arun Jaitley, the Secretary, Department of Economic Affairs, Shri Shaktikanta Das and the President, CII, Shri Naushad Forbes.jpg|thumb|Das (right) with [[Minister of Finance (India)|Minister of Finance]] [[Arun Jaitley]] (centre) and the president of [[Confederation of Indian Industry]] [[Naushad Forbes]] (left)]]\n\n==== Economic Affairs Secretary ====\nDas was appointed [[Economic Affairs Secretary|Union Economic Affairs Secretary]] by the ACC in {{Date|August 2014|dmy}},<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/shaktikanta-das-appointed-economic-affairs-secretary-hasmukh-adhia-is-new-revenue-secretary/articleshow/48715974.cms|title=Shaktikanta Das appointed Economic Affairs Secretary; Hasmukh Adhia is new Revenue Secretary|last=|first=|date=August 29, 2015|website=[[The Economic Times]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/das-is-new-economic-affairs-secy-hasmukh-adhia-revenue-secretary/|title=Das is new economic affairs secy, Hasmukh Adhia revenue secretary|date=August 29, 2015|website=[[The Indian Express]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|oclc=70274541|access-date=January 15, 2018|agency=Express News Service}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/shaktikanta-das-takes-charge-as-economic-affairs-secretary-1213313|title=Shaktikanta Das Takes Charge as Economic Affairs Secretary|last=|first=|date=September 2, 2015|website=[[NDTV]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref> he assumed the office of Secretary on {{Date|2015-08-31|dmy}},<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> and admitted it and simultaneously [[Pension|superannuated]] from service on {{Date|2017-05-28|dmy}},<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> after being given a three-month{{Nbsp}}extension by the government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/business/DEA-Secretary-Shaktikanta-Das-gets-3-month-extension/article17083022.ece|title=DEA Secretary Shaktikanta Das gets 3-month extension|last=|first=|date=January 23, 2017|website=[[The Hindu]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/dea-secretary-shaktikanta-das-gets-3-month-extension-117012301178_1.html|title=DEA Secretary Shaktikanta Das gets 3-month extension|last=|first=|date=January 23, 2017|website=[[Business Standard]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/govt-extends-economic-affairs-secretary-shaktikanta-das-tenure-by-3-months/articleshow/56738856.cms|title=Govt extends Economic Affairs Secretary Shaktikanta Das' tenure by 3 months|last=|first=|date=January 24, 2017|website=[[The Economic Times]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring his tenure as [[Secretary to Government of India|Union Economic Affairs Secretary]], Das was widely regarded as one of the most powerful civil servants in India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/modi-government-bureaucrats-ajit-doval-nripendra-misra-s-jaishankar/1/927889.html|title=The game changers|last=Unnithan|first=Sandeep|date=April 13, 2017|website=[[India Today]]|issn=0254-8399|access-date=11 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/the-crack-team-those-who-made-gst-a-reality/shaktikanta-das-former-revenue-and-economic-affairs-secretary/slideshow/59400919.cms|title=The crack team: Those who made GST a reality - Shaktikanta Das, Former Revenue and Economic Affairs Secretary|date=1 July 2017|website=[[The Economic Times]]|publisher=[[The Times Group]]|oclc=61311680|access-date=11 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Post retirement ===\nPost his retirement from the IAS, Das was appointed a member of the [[Fifteenth Finance Commission|Fifteenth{{Nbsp}}Finance Commission]] by the ACC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/n-k-singh-heads-15th-finance-commission-shaktikanta-das-a-member-117112701199_1.html|title=N.K. Singh heads 15th Finance Commission, Shaktikanta Das a member|last=|first=|date=November 27, 2017|website=[[Business Standard]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/nk-singh-appointed-chairman-of-15th-finance-commission/article9974029.ece|title=NK Singh appointed Chairman of 15th Finance Commission|last=|first=|date=November 27, 2017|website=Business Line|publisher=[[The Hindu]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/rWfJyCZBIkttQMKHXoZBHO/NK-Singh-appointed-chairman-of-15th-Finance-Commission.html|title=N.K. Singh appointed chairman of 15th Finance Commission|last=|first=|date=November 27, 2017|website=Livemint|publisher=[[HT Media Ltd]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/former-planning-commission-member-nk-singh-appointed-15th-finance-commission-chairman-1780855|title=Former Planning Commission Member NK Singh Appointed 15th Finance Commission Chairman|last=|first=|date=November 28, 2017|website=[[NDTV]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref> In addition, he was appointed as India's [[Sherpa (emissary)|Sherpa]] to the [[G20]] by the ACC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/former-dea-secretary-shaktikanta-das-confirmed-as-g-20-sherpa-117112800060_1.html|title=Former DEA secretary Shaktikanta Das confirmed as G-20 sherpa|last=|first=|date=November 28, 2017|website=[[Business Standard]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/shaktikanta-das-appointed-indias-g20-sherpa-until-december-31-2018/949913/|title=Shaktikanta Das appointed India\u2019s G20 Sherpa until December 31, 2018|date=November 27, 2017|website=[[The Financial Express (India)|The Financial Express]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/shaktikanta-das-appointed-as-indias-g20-sherpa/articleshow/61823581.cms|title=Shaktikanta Das appointed as India's G20 Sherpa. On 12th December, 2018, he has been appointed as the 25th Governor of the Reserve Bank of India for a period of three years.|last=|first=|date=November 27, 2017|website=[[The Times of India]]|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=live|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref> In {{Date|December 2018|dmy}}, on his appointment as the governor of the Reserve Bank of India, Das resigned from his position in the Fifteenth{{Nbsp}}Finance Commission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dea.gov.in/sites/default/files/Acceptance%20of%20resignation%20of%20Shri%20Shaktikanta%20Das-Member,%20FFC-11-12-2018.PDF|title=Acceptance of resignation of Shri Shaktikanta Das-Member, FFC|date=11 December 2018|website=[[Department of Economic Affairs (India)|Department of Economic Affairs]], [[Ministry of Finance (India)|Ministry of Finance]], [[Government of India]]|access-date=16 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Governor of Reserve Bank of India ====\nDas was appointed [[List of Governors of Reserve Bank of India|Governor of the Reserve Bank of India]] by the ACC on {{Date|2018-12-11|dmy}} for a period of three{{Nbsp}}years, replacing [[Urjit Patel]] who had resigned the day before.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/Industry/mqqkVZgURWChvJbxq45E4H/Shaktikanta-Das-appointed-new-RBI-governor.html|title=Shaktikanta Das, who oversaw demonetization, is new RBI governor|last=Prasad|first=Gireesh Chandra|last2=Ghosh|first2=Shayan|date=11 December 2018|website=[[Livemint]]|publisher=Vivek Khanna|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]/[[Mumbai]]|access-date=12 December 2018|last3=Gopakumar|first3=Gopika}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/business/shaktikanta-das-is-new-rbi-governor|title=Shaktikanta Das Is New RBI Governor|date=11 December 2018|website=[[BloombergQuint]]|others=BQ Desk|access-date=11 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/banking/finance/banking/shaktikanta-das-the-man-behind-gst-note-ban-now-heads-rbi/articleshow/67046113.cms|title=Shaktikanta Das: The man behind GST, note ban now heads RBI|date=11 December 2018|work=[[The Economic Times]]|access-date=11 December 2018|publisher=[[The Times Group]]|others=ET Online|oclc=61311680}}</ref>\n\nDas' appointment as RBI governor received mostly positive responses,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/how-shaktikanta-das-may-aid-regain-overseas-investor-confidence/articleshow/67049476.cms|title=How Shaktikanta Das may aid regain overseas investor confidence|last=Das|first=Saikat|date=11 December 2018|work=[[The Economic Times]]|access-date=12 December 2018|publisher=[[The Times Group]]|publication-place=[[Mumbai]]|oclc=61311680}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://in.reuters.com/article/india-cenbank-governor-idINKBN1OA1N0|title=Expert Views: India appoints Shaktikanta Das as RBI governor|last=Kurup|first=Krishna V.|date=11 December 2018|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=12 December 2018|agency=[[Reuters]]|last2=Thomas|first2=Chris|editor-last=Miglani|editor-first=Sanjeev|publication-place=[[Bengaluru]]/[[New Delhi]]|last3=Monnappa|first3=Chandini|last4=Dasgupta|first4=Neha|editor2-first=Sai Sachin|editor2-last=Ravikumar}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/business/Economy/has-handled-all-his-assignments-well/article25720280.ece|title=\u2018Shaktikanta Das handled all his assignments well\u2019|date=11 December 2018|work=[[The Hindu]]|access-date=12 December 2018|publisher=[[N. Ram]]|others=Special Correspondent|publication-place=[[Chennai]]|issn=0971-751X|oclc=13119119}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/economy/mit-economist-abhijit-banerjee-flays-government-in-appointing-shaktikanta-das-as-rbi-governor/1411091/|title=MIT economist Abhijit Banerjee flays government in appointing Shaktikanta Das as RBI Governor|date=11 December 2018|website=[[The Financial Express (India)|The Financial Express]]|oclc=30000665|access-date=12 December 2018|agency=[[Press Trust of India]]}}</ref> with [[DBS Bank]]'s head of markets for India at Singapore, Ashish Vaidya, saying that previous governors of the RBI with an [[Indian Administrative Service|IAS]] background, such as [[Y. Venugopal Reddy]] and [[Duvvuri Subbarao]], had been successful and that Das' \"cordial relations with the government [...] [would] likely help policy negotiations.\"<ref name=\":2\" /> [[S. S. Mundra]], a former [[Deputy Governor of the Reserve Bank of India|deputy governor]] of the RBI, said Das was a \"good and balanced choice\" for RBI governorship and had \"a good understanding of the whole of the financial sector both from the ministry and also in his interactions with the RBI.\"<ref name=\":5\" />  A former [[Governor of the Reserve Bank of India]] [[C. Rangarajan]], said Das had \"experience in economic affairs\" and would \"make a good governor\".<ref name=\":6\" /> Gaurav Shah, a senior vice president at [[Geojit Financial Services]], said \"a name like Shaktikanta Das carries track record, experience, credentials, credibility and respect along with him.\"<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nOn the other hand, Nobel laureate and professor at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], [[Abhijit Banerjee]], said Das' appointment posed a lot of \"frightening\" questions on governance of autonomous public institutions.<ref name=\":3\" /> [[Subramanian Swamy]], a member of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]], the largest party of the ruling [[National Democratic Alliance (India)|National Democratic Alliance]] [[Coalition government|coalition]], and a nominated [[Member of parliament, Rajya Sabha|member of the Rajya Sabha]] (Council of the States), criticised Das, calling him a \"corrupt person\" at an event at the [[Indian School of Business]] in [[Hyderabad]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/rbi-governor-saktikanta-das-highly-corrupt-says-swamy/cid/1679687|title=RBI chief Saktikanta Das 'corrupt', says Swamy|date=23 December 2018|website=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]|publication-place=[[Hyderabad]]|oclc=271717941|access-date=24 December 2018|agency=[[Press Trust of India]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/latest/906736/subramanian-swamy-claims-new-rbi-governor-shaktikanta-das-is-a-corrupt-person|title=Subramanian Swamy claims new RBI governor Shaktikanta Das is a \u2018corrupt person\u2019|date=23 December 2018|website=[[Scroll.in]]|others=Scroll Staff|access-date=24 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nDas assumed charge as RBI governor on {{Date|2018-12-12|dmy}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/business/rbi-governor-shaktikanta-das-takes-charge-seen-as-a-safe-bet-by-govt-new-chief-of-mint-street-starts-on-a-weak-wicket-5715031.html|title=RBI governor Shaktikanta Das takes charge: Seen as a safe bet by govt, new chief of Mint Street starts on a weak wicket|last=Kaul|first=Vivek|date=12 December 2018|website=[[Firstpost]]|publisher=[[Network 18]]|access-date=12 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/shaktikanta-das-takes-charge-as-25th-governor-of-the-rbi/articleshow/67054312.cms|title=Shaktikanta Das takes charge as 25th Governor of the RBI|date=12 December 2018|work=[[The Economic Times]]|access-date=12 December 2018|publisher=[[The Times Group]]|others=ET Online|oclc=61311680}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/rbi-governor/shaktikanta-das-takes-charge-as-25th-rbi-governor|title=Shaktikanta Das Takes Charge As 25th RBI Governor|date=12 December 2018|website=[[BloombergQuint]]|others=BQ Desk|access-date=12 December 2018}}</ref> Reactions of the markets to Das' appointment was positive, with [[BSE SENSEX]] gaining 629{{Nbsp}}points and [[NIFTY 50]] increasing by 188{{Nbsp}}points.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/markets-end-higher-as-new-rbi-chief-takes-charge-sensex-surges-629-points/articleshow/67058356.cms|title=Markets end higher as new RBI chief takes charge, Sensex surges 629 points|date=12 December 2018|website=[[The Times of India]]|publisher=[[Bennett, Coleman & Co. Ltd.]]|others=TIMESOFINDIA.COM|publication-place=[[New Delhi]]|oclc=23379369|access-date=12 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/Money/OOEBbhmz7RJAHSO8q5ceuO/Markets-LIVE-Sensex-Nifty-set-for-cautious-start.html|title=Closing bell: Sensex surges 629 points, Nifty above 10,700 after RBI chief appointment|date=12 December 2018|website=[[Mint (newspaper)|Livemint]]|publisher=Vivek Khanna|others=Livemint|publication-place=[[Mumbai]]|access-date=12 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/market/sensex-nifty-post-biggest-1-day-gain-in-5-weeks-here-are-3-key-reasons-behind-surge/1411869/|title=Sensex, Nifty post biggest 1-day gain in 5 weeks; here are 3 key reasons behind surge|date=12 December 2018|website=[[The Financial Express (India)|The Financial Express]]|others=FE Online|oclc=30000665|access-date=12 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lh1yWyFuLQI|title=Who is the new RBI Governor|date=December 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs RBI governor, Das serves as the ''ex-officio'' chairperson of the [[Monetary Policy Committee (India)|Monetary Policy Committee]] of the central bank.<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/newly-appointed-deputy-governor-to-look-after-rbi-s-monetary-policy-division-11579097609165.html|title=Newly appointed deputy governor to look after RBI's monetary policy division|date=2020-01-15|website=[[Livemint]]|publisher=Vivek Khanna|language=en|publication-place=[[Mumbai]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-16|agency=[[Press Trust of India]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/banking/finance/banking/rbi-appoints-ed-janak-raj-as-member-of-mpc/articleshow/73741480.cms|title=RBI appoints ED Janak Raj as member of MPC|date=2020-01-29|work=[[The Economic Times]]|access-date=2020-04-03|url-status=live|agency=[[Press Trust of India]]|publication-place=[[Mumbai]]|issn=0013-0389|oclc=61311680}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Shaktikanta Das}}\n*{{URL|1=https://supremo.nic.in/ERSheetHtml.aspx?OffIDErhtml=14205&PageId=|2=Executive record sheet, as maintained by the Department of Personnel and Training of the Ministry of Personnel, Public Grievances and Pensions of the Government of India}}\n*{{URL|1=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=27531155&privcapId=882940|2=Executive profile, as maintained by Bloomberg}}\n\n{{Governors of Reserve Bank of India}}\n{{G20-CBGovernors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Das, Shaktikanta}}\n[[Category:Indian Administrative Service officers]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Bhubaneswar]]\n[[Category:Governors of the Reserve Bank of India]]\n[[Category:Indian diplomats]]\n[[Category:St. Stephen's College, Delhi alumni]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4064:258d:4f17:edd0:78ba:9c29:b0b7", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Cast of shashikant Das)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shaktikanta_Das"}
{"title_page": "Ivan Milat", "text_new": "{{short description|Convicted murderer (b. 1944, d. 2019)}}{{Lead too short|date=February 2020}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox serial killer\n| name = \n| image = Ivan Milat.jpg\n| caption = Milat's 1971 [[mug shot]]\n| birth_name = Ivan Robert Marko Milat\n| signature = Ivan_milat_signature.png\n| alias = \"Bill\"<br>The Backpacker Killer<br>The Backpacker Murderer\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1944|12|27|}}\n| birth_place = {{NSWcity|Guildford}}, [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2019|10|27|1944|12|27|}}\n| death_place = [[Long Bay Correctional Centre]]<br/>[[Matraville, New South Wales]], Australia\n| nationality = Australian\n| known_for = [[Backpacker murders]]\n| victims = 7\n| weapons = [[.22 LR|.22 calibre]] [[Ruger 10/22]]<br>\n[[Bowie knife]]\n| country = Australian\n| states = [[New South Wales]]\n| employer = [[Roads & Traffic Authority]]\n| beginyear = 1989\n| endyear = 1993\n| apprehended = 22 May 1994\n| conviction = 7 counts [[murder]] (27 July 1996)<br>\n1 count [[attempted murder]] (27 July 1996)<br>\n1 count [[false imprisonment]] (27 July 1996)<br>\n1 count [[robbery]] (27 July 1996)\n| sentence = 7 [[life sentences]] without parole ([[murder]])<br>\n6 years imprisonment ([[attempted murder]])<br>\n6 years imprisonment ([[false imprisonment]])<br>\n6 years imprisonment ([[robbery]])\n| conviction_status = Deceased\n| imprisoned = [[Long Bay Correctional Centre]] (2019-d)<br>\n[[Goulburn Correctional Centre]] (1997-2019)<br>\n[[Maitland Gaol]] (1996-1997)\n}}\n'''Ivan Robert Marko Milat''' (27 December 1944 \u2013 27 October 2019<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Malcolm|last2=Feneley|first2=Rick|title=Life never a picnic for the dirt-poor, troubled Milat clan|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/life-never-a-picnic-for-the-dirtpoor-troubled-milat-clan-20101123-185r8.html|accessdate=1 April 2017|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=24 November 2010}}</ref>) was an Australian serial killer who was convicted of the [[backpacker murders]] in 1996. Ivan left his White truck to his nephew, Shannon Milat, who continues to live out of it to this day.\n\n==Early life==\nIvan Milat was the son of a [[Croats|Croatian]] emigrant and labourer, Stjepan Marko \"Steven\" Milat (1902\u20131983), and an Australian, Margaret Elizabeth Piddleston (1920\u20132001), who married when she was 16.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Malcolm|last2=Feneley|first2=Rick|title=Life never a picnic for the dirt-poor, troubled Milat clan|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/life-never-a-picnic-for-the-dirtpoor-troubled-milat-clan-20101123-185r8.html|accessdate=26 January 2018|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=24 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kennedy|first1=Les|title=Does crime run in the Milat family tree?|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/does-crime-run-in-the-milat-family-tree-20101127-18bg2.html|accessdate=25 January 2018|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=28 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heavenaddress.com/restingplace/margaret-elizabeth-milat/278434|title=Margaret Elizabeth Milat \u2013 HeavenAddress Resting Place|website=www.heavenaddress.com|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref> Milat was the fifth-born of their 14 children,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|last1=Kennedy|first1=Les|title=Milat case stalked by uncertainty|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/stalked-by-uncertainty/2005/07/20/1121539033488.html|accessdate=25 January 2018|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=21 July 2005}}</ref> and the growing family first lived in [[Bossley Park]] before relocating to [[Liverpool, New South Wales|Liverpool]]. Many of the 10 Milat boys were well known to local police, and Milat displayed antisocial behaviour at a young age, leading to a stint in a residential school at age 13.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://casefilepodcast.com/case-109-belanglo-part-3/|title=Case 109: Belanglo (Part 3)|date=6 April 2019|publisher=}}</ref> By 17, he was in a juvenile detention centre for theft, and at 19, was involved in a shop break in.<ref name=\":2\" /> In 1964, he was sentenced to 18 months for a break and enter, and a month after release, he was arrested for driving a stolen car and was sentenced to 2 years hard labour.<ref name=\":2\" /> In September 1967, aged 23, he was sentenced to 3 years for theft.<ref name=\":2\" /> In April 1971, he was charged with the abduction of two 18 year-old hitchhikers and the rape of one of them.<ref name=\"Bio\">{{cite web|title=Ivan Milat Biography|url=http://www.biography.com/people/ivan-milat-17169710|work=[[The Biography Channel]]|publisher=A+E Television Networks, LLC.|accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref> While awaiting trial, he was involved in a string of robberies with some of his brothers, before faking his suicide and fleeing to New Zealand for a year.<ref name=\":2\" /> He was rearrested in 1974, but the robbery and kidnap cases against him failed at trial with the help of the Milat's family lawyer, [[John Marsden (lawyer)|John Marsden]]. He took on a job as a truck driver in 1975, and by the time of the [[Belanglo State Forest]] crimes, Milat had worked on and off for 20 years for the [[Roads & Traffic Authority]] all over the state.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Backpacker murders==\n{{main|Backpacker murders}}\n\n===Background===\nBy the time of the first Belanglo State Forest discoveries, several backpackers had been reported missing. One case involved a young [[Victoria (Australia)|Victorian]] couple from [[Frankston, Victoria|Frankston]], Deborah Everist (19) and James Gibson (19), who had been missing since leaving Sydney for [[ConFest]], near Albury, on 30 December 1989.<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://casefilepodcast.com/case-109-belanglo-part-1/|title=Case 109: Belanglo (Part 1)|date=2019-03-23|website=Casefile: True Crime Podcast|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-31}}</ref> Another related to Simone Schmidl (21), from Germany, who had been missing since leaving Sydney for Melbourne on 20 January 1991.<ref name=\":32\" /> Similarly, a German couple, Gabor Neugebauer (21) and Anja Habschied (20), had disappeared after leaving a [[Kings Cross, New South Wales|Kings Cross]] hostel for Mildura on 26 December 1991. Another involved missing British backpackers Caroline Clarke (21) and Joanne Walters (22), who were last seen in Kings Cross on 18 April 1992.<ref name=\"Sorrow\">{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/friends-born-of-sorrow/2006/04/23/1145730809381.html'?page=fullpage|title=Friends born of sorrow|last=Meacham|first=Steve|date=24 April 2006|newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Discovery of victims ===\n[[File:Belanglo_State_Forest_sign.jpg|right|thumb|A sign at the entrance to the Belanglo State Forest]]\nOn 19 September 1992, two runners discovered a concealed corpse while [[orienteering]] in Belanglo.<ref name=\"25yearsago2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/twenty-five-years-ago-the-first-victims-of-backpacker-killer-ivan-milat-were-found-in-belanglo-forest-twenty-five-years-ago-the-first-victims-of-backpacker-killer-ivan-milat-were-found-in-belanglo-forest/news-story/f4a31abad223faa68d8d73ca054d297e|title=Twenty five years ago the first victims of Backpacker Killer Ivan Milat were found in Belanglo Forest|last1=Lennon|first1=Troy|date=19 September 2017|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]}}</ref> The following morning, police discovered a second body {{convert|30|m|ft}} from the first.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=acfCYGPaqCoC&pg=PT322|title=Sins of the Brother: The Definitive Story of Ivan Milat and the Backpacker Murders|last1=Whittaker|first1=Mark|last2=Kennedy|first2=Les|date=10 November 2007|publisher=Pan Macmillan Australia|isbn=978-0-330-36284-9|pages=267\u2013268, 322|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref> Police quickly confirmed, via dental records, that the bodies were those of Clarke and Walters.<ref name=\":32\" /> A search of the area failed to uncover any of the other missing backpackers.\n\nIn October 1993, however, a local man searching for firewood discovered bones in a particularly remote section of the forest.<ref name=\"Brown20002\">{{cite book|title=Bombs, Guns and Knives: Violent Crime in Australia|last=Brown|first=Malcolm|publisher=New Holland|year=2000|isbn=1-86436-668-0|location=Sydney|pages=148\u2013153}}</ref> He returned with police to the scene where two bodies were quickly discovered and later identified as Gibson and Everist. The presence of Gibson's body in Belanglo puzzled investigators as his camera and backpack had previously been discovered at [[Galston Gorge]], over {{convert|120|km}} to the north.<ref name=\"Sorrow\" /><ref name=\":32\" />\n\nOn 1 November 1993, a skeleton was found in a clearing along a fire trail in the forest during a police sweep.<ref name=\"Timeline2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.crimeandinvestigation.co.uk/crime-files/ivan-milat/timeline.html|title=Timeline|work=[[Crime & Investigation Network]]|publisher=AETN UK|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref> It was later identified as that of Schmidl.<ref name=\"Sorrow\" /> Clothing found at the scene was not Schmidl's, but matched that of another missing backpacker, Habschied.<ref name=\":32\" /> On 4 November 1993, the bodies of Habschied and Neugebauer were then found on a nearby fire trail in shallow graves {{convert|50|m}} apart.<ref name=\"Nine\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/archive/news/the-nine-bodies-found-in-belanglo-forest/story-e6frg6o6-1225958668442|title=The nine bodies found in Belanglo forest|date=22 November 2010|newspaper=[[The Australian]]|accessdate=13 January 2014|agency=[[Australian Associated Press|AAP]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Search for a serial killer ===\nExamination of the remains showed evidence that some of the victims had been tortured and did not die instantly from their injuries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-48346543|title=The 'backpacker killer' and unanswered questions|last=Nunn|first=Gary|date=27 October 2019|via=www.bbc.com|accessdate=27 October 2019}}</ref> In response, on 14 October 1993, Task Force Air, containing more than 20 detectives and analysts, was set up by the [[New South Wales Police Force|NSW Police]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://casefilepodcast.com/case-109-belanglo-part-2/|title=Case 109: Belanglo (Part 2) cebo|date=30 March 2019|website=Casefile: True Crime Podcast}}</ref> On 5 November 1993, the NSW government increased the reward in relation to the killings to $500,000.<ref name=\":1\" /> After developing their [[Offender profiling|profile]] of the killer, the police faced an enormous volume of data from numerous sources.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aic.gov.au/media_library/conferences/outlook4/mouzos.pdf|title=Investigating Homicide: New Responses for an Old Crime|last=Mouzos|first=Jenny|work=[[Australian Institute of Criminology]]|publisher=Australian Government|page=5|format=PDF|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref> Investigators applied [[link analysis]] technology, and as a result, the list of suspects was narrowed from a short list of 230 to an even shorter list of 32.<ref>{{cite book|title=Machine Learning Forensics for Law Enforcement, Security, and Intelligence|last=Mena|first=Jes\u00fas|publisher=CRC Press (Taylor & Francis Group)|year=2011|isbn=978-1-4398-6069-4|location=Boca Raton, FL}}</ref> Speculation arose that the crimes were the work of several killers,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dDOW75aJMR8C&pg=PA313|title=Encyclopedia of Murder and Violent Crime|last=Hickey|first=Eric W.|date=22 July 2003|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-0-7619-2437-1|page=313|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/australasia/did-australias-backpacker-killer-have-an-accomplice-2198469.html|title=Did Australia's backpacker killer have an accomplice?|last=Maynard|first=Roger|date=30 January 2011|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref> given that most of the victims had been attacked while as pairs, had been killed in different ways, and buried separately.\n\nOn 13 November 1993, police received a call from Paul Onions (24) in the U.K. On 25 January 1990, Onions had been backpacking in Australia and, while hitchhiking from [[Liverpool railway station, Sydney|Liverpool station]] towards [[Mildura]], had accepted a ride south out of [[Casula, New South Wales|Casula]] from a man known only as \"Bill\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/belanglo-state-forest-once-again-the-home-of-nightmarish-murder/news-story/16f26fd7b5a8d83d658b15059a780435|title=Belanglo State Forest once again the home of nightmarish murder|last1=Starick|first1=Paul|date=22 October 2015|work=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]|accessdate=26 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Newton20062\">{{cite book|last=Newton|first=Michael|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DwNVbOcTncwC&pg=PA178|title=The Encyclopedia of Serial Killers|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-0-8160-6987-3|pages=178\u2013179|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref> South of the town of [[Mittagong]], and less than 1&nbsp;km from Belanglo State Forest, Bill stopped and pulled out a revolver and some ropes stating it was a robbery, at which point Onions managed to flee.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/law-order/true-crime-scene/backpacker-murders-how-backpacker-paul-onions-survived-a-close-encounter-with-evil-ivan-milat/news-story/440554edab618a9bcf8ea0de17c3a21b|title=Backpacker murders: How backpacker Paul Onions survived a close encounter with evil Ivan Milat|date=15 May 2015|work=Herald Sun|accessdate=26 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/tv-reviews/born-to-kill--ivan-milat/2006/07/25/1153746844314.html|title=Born to Kill \u2013 Ivan Milat|last=Oliver|first=Robin|date=26 July 2006|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=11 January 2014}}</ref> Onions flagged down a passing motorist, and together they described the assailant and his vehicle to the [[Bowral]] police.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/national/backpacker-who-escaped-ivan-milat-to-return-to-australia/story-e6freooo-1225825004932|title=Backpacker who escaped Ivan Milat to return to Australia|last=Murray|first=David|date=31 January 2010|newspaper=[[The Courier-Mail]]|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref> On 13 April 1994, detectives re-found the note regarding Onions' call. Onions' statement was corroborated by Berry, along with the girlfriend of a man who worked with Milat.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/on-the-trail-of-a--serial-killer-20140413-36m7u.html|title=On the trail of a ... serial killer|last1=Small|first1=Clive|date=19 April 2014|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=26 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Arrest and trial===\nOn 26 February 1994, police surveillance of the Milat house at Cinnabar Street, {{NSWcity|Eagle Vale}} commenced.<ref name=\":2\" /> Police learnt that Milat had recently sold his silver [[Nissan Patrol]] four-wheel drive shortly after the discovery of the bodies of Clarke and Walters.<ref>{{cite book|last=Marriott|first=Trevor|title=The Evil Within \u2013 A Top Murder Squad Detective Reveals The Chilling True Stories of The World's Most Notorious Killers|url=https://archive.org/details/evilwithintopmur0000marr|url-access=registration|accessdate=10 January 2014|date=4 September 2013|publisher=John Blake Publishing|isbn=978-1-78219-365-4|page=[https://archive.org/details/evilwithintopmur0000marr/page/21 21]}}</ref> Police also confirmed that Milat had not been working on any of the days of the attacks<ref name=\":3\" /> and acquaintances also told police about Milat's obsession with weapons.<ref name=\"25yearsago\">{{cite news|last1=Lennon|first1=Troy|title=Twenty five years ago the first victims of Backpacker Killer Ivan Milat were found in Belanglo Forest|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/twenty-five-years-ago-the-first-victims-of-backpacker-killer-ivan-milat-were-found-in-belanglo-forest-twenty-five-years-ago-the-first-victims-of-backpacker-killer-ivan-milat-were-found-in-belanglo-forest/news-story/f4a31abad223faa68d8d73ca054d297e|accessdate=26 January 2018|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=19 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Chapman|first=Simon|title=Over Our Dead Bodies: Port Arthur and Australia's Fight for Gun Control|url=http://ses.library.usyd.edu.au/bitstream/2123/8938/1/Over-our-dead-bodies_Chapman.pdf|accessdate=10 January 2014|year=2013|publisher=Sydney University Press|isbn=978-1-74332-031-0|page=163}}</ref> When the connection between the Belanglo murders and Onions' experience was made, Onions flew to Australia to help with the investigation.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Small|first1=Clive|title=On the trail of a ... serial killer|url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/on-the-trail-of-a--serial-killer-20140413-36m7u.html|accessdate=26 January 2018|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=19 April 2014}}</ref> On 5 May 1994, Onions positively identified Milat as the man who had picked him up and attempted to assault him.<ref name=\"Brown2000\">{{cite book|last=Brown|first=Malcolm|title=Bombs, Guns and Knives: Violent Crime in Australia|year=2000|publisher=New Holland|location=Sydney|isbn=1-86436-668-0|pages=148\u2013153}}</ref>\n\nMilat was arrested at his home on 22 May 1994 on robbery and weapon charges related to the Onions attack after 50 police officers surrounded the house.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/serial_killers/predators/milat/discovery_1.html |title=Ivan Milat: The Last Ride|last=Bellamy |first=Patrick|work=[[TruTV]]|publisher=Time Warner Inc.|pages=12\u201313|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110091143/http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/serial_killers/predators/milat/discovery_1.html|archivedate=10 January 2014 |url-status=dead|accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Timeline\">{{cite web|title=Timeline|url=http://www.crimeandinvestigation.co.uk/crime-files/ivan-milat/timeline.html|work=[[Crime & Investigation Network]]|publisher=AETN UK|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref> The search of Milat's home revealed various weapons, including a [[.22 LR|.22-calibre]] [[J. G. Ansch\u00fctz|Ansch\u00fctz Model 1441/42]] rifle and parts of a .22 calibre [[Ruger 10/22]] rifle that matched the type used in the murders, a [[Browning Arms Company|Browning pistol]], and a [[Bowie knife]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://casefilepodcast.com/case-109-belanglo-part-4/|title=Case 109: Belanglo (Part 4)|date=2019-04-13|website=Casefile: True Crime Podcast|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> Also uncovered were items belonging to several of his victims.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Ivan Milat |url=http://www.citv.com.au/crime-profiles/44/ivan-milat/3/the-crime |work=Crime & Investigation Network |publisher=Foxtel |accessdate=10 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110092804/http://www.citv.com.au/crime-profiles/44/ivan-milat/3/the-crime |archivedate=10 January 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> Homes belonging to his mother and five of his brothers were also searched,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nVJD6V0XAtwC&pg=PT344|title=Australia's Serial Killers|last=Kidd|first=Paul B.|date=1 August 2011|publisher=Pan Macmillan Australia|isbn=978-1-74262-798-4|page=344|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref> uncovering several more items belonging to the victims.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nMilat appeared in court on 23 May, but he did not enter a [[plea]].<ref name=\"Dispatch\">{{cite news|last=Spielman|first=Peter James|title=Suspect charged in seven murders|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1734&dat=19940531&id=MOAhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=1VIEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6928,2645168|accessdate=13 January 2014|newspaper=[[The Dispatch (Lexington)|The Dispatch]]|date=31 May 1994|agency=[[Associated Press|AP]]}}</ref> On 31 May, Milat was also charged with the seven backpacker murders.<ref name=\":4\" /> On 28 June, Milat sacked his defence lawyer, Marsden, and sought legal aid to pay for his defence.<ref name=\":4\" /> Meanwhile, brothers Richard and Walter were tried in relation to weapons, drugs and stolen items found on their properties.<ref name=\":4\" /> A [[Committal procedure|committal hearing]] for Milat regarding the murders began on 24 October and lasted until 12 December, during which over 200 witnesses appeared.<ref name=\":4\" /> Based on the evidence, at the beginning of February 1995, Milat was remanded in custody until June that same year.\n\nOn 26 March 1996, the trial opened at the [[Supreme Court of New South Wales]] and was prosecuted by [[Mark Tedeschi]].<ref name=\"Trial\">{{cite web|title=The Trial|url=http://www.crimeandinvestigation.co.uk/crime-files/ivan-milat/trial.html|work=Crime & Investigation Network|publisher=AETN UK|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref> His defence argued that, in spite of the evidence, there was no non-circumstantial proof Milat was guilty and attempted to shift the blame to other members of his family, particularly Richard.<ref name=\"Trial\" /> 145 witnesses took the stand, including members of the Milat family who endeavoured to provide alibis, and, on 18 June, Milat himself.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://casefilepodcast.com/case-109-belanglo-part-5/|title=Case 109: Belanglo (Part 5)|date=2019-04-20|website=Casefile: True Crime Podcast|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> On 27 July 1996, after 18 weeks of testimony, a jury found Milat guilty of the murders.<ref name=\"Timeline\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Walker|first=Frank|title=Milat's brother claims police still treating him as murder suspect|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/05/22/1085176039666.html?from=storylhs|accessdate=11 January 2014|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=23 May 2004}}</ref> He was given a [[life imprisonment|life sentence]] on each count without the possibility of parole. He was also convicted of the attempted murder, false imprisonment and robbery of Onions, for which he received six years [[jail]] each.<ref name=\"Newton2006\">{{cite book|last=Newton|first=Michael|title=The Encyclopedia of Serial Killers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DwNVbOcTncwC&pg=PA178|accessdate=13 January 2014|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-0-8160-6987-3|pages=178\u2013179}}</ref>\n\n== Incarceration and appeals ==\nOn his first day, when arriving at [[Maitland Gaol]], Milat was beaten by another inmate.<ref>{{cite news|title=Skeleton key to unlock Ivan Milat mystery?|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/skeleton-key-to-unlock-ivan-milat-mystery/story-e6frf7jo-1225912001007|accessdate=10 January 2014|newspaper=[[Herald Sun]]|date=30 August 2010|agency=AAP}}</ref> Almost a year later, on 16 May 1997, he made an escape attempt alongside convicted drug dealer and former Sydney councillor George Savvas.<ref>{{cite news|title=Maitland Correctional Centre Escape Attempt |url=http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/parlment/hansart.nsf/V3Key/LA19970520013 |accessdate=10 January 2014 |newspaper=[[Parliament of New South Wales]] |date=20 May 1997 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110094731/http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/parlment/hansart.nsf/V3Key/LA19970520013 |archivedate=10 January 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> The plan failed and Savvas was found hanged in his cell the next day, and Milat was transferred to the maximum security section at [[Goulburn Correctional Centre]] in [[Goulburn, New South Wales]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Skeleton key to unlock Ivan Milat mystery?|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/skeleton-key-to-unlock-ivan-milat-mystery/news-story/bb675c84c1205e881219048b5b479bf7|accessdate=25 January 2018|work=Herald Sun|agency=AAP|date=30 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn November 1997, Milat appealed against his convictions due to a breach of his common law right to legal representation, as established in ''[[Dietrich v The Queen]]''. However, the [[New South Wales Court of Criminal Appeal]] dismissed the appeal.<ref name=\"Case\">{{cite AustLII|NSWSC|795|1998|litigants=Regina v Milat |date=26 February 1998}}.</ref> In 2004, Milat filed an application with the [[High Court of Australia]] that he be allowed special leave to appeal on new grounds. The application for leave was ultimately dismissed, affirming the Court of Criminal Appeal's decision to disallow his initial appeal.<ref>{{Cite AustLII|HCA|17|2004|litigants=Milat v The Queen |parallelcite=(2004) 205 [[Australian Law Reports|ALR]] 338; (2004) 78 [[Australian Law Journal Reports|ALJR]] |date=24 February 2004}}.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/05/28/1085641690085.html|title=Serial killer Milat loses conviction appeal|agency=AAP|date=28 May 2004|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=20 May 2017}}</ref> On 27 October 2005, in the NSW Supreme Court<ref>{{Cite AustLII|NSWSC|920|2005|litigants=R v Milat (backpacker murders)|date=27 October 2005}}.</ref> Milat's final avenue of appeal was refused.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/4415216.stm|title=Serial killer's appeal is refused|date=7 November 2005|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref> In 2006, two other application attempts were rejected as well, as was one in November 2011.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nIn 2001, following the opening of the High Risk Management Corrections Centre (Supermax) at Goulburn Correctional Centre, Milat was transferred from the maximum security section of the prison into one of its 45 new units.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Australia\u2019s worst serial killer Ivan Milat has died aged 74|url=https://www.news.com.au/national/australias-worst-serial-killer-ivan-milat-has-died-aged-74/news-story/c0ec9be649b146fc3919ce05387b475d|accessdate=29 October 2019|work=[[News.com.au]]|date=27 October 2019}}</ref> In 2006, a toaster and TV given to Milat in his cell caused a public outcry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/milat-gets-tv-toaster-returned-to-cell-20060715-gdnyv3.html|title=Milat gets TV, toaster returned to cell|date=2006-07-14|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Health and death ==\nOn 26 January 2009, Milat cut off his little finger with a plastic knife, with the intention of mailing it to the [[High Court of Australia]] to force an appeal.<ref name=\"finger\">{{cite news|url=http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-national/medics-unable-to-reattach-milats-finger-20090127-7qg5.html|title=Medics unable to reattach Milat's finger|date=27 January 2009|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=27 January 2009|agency=AAP}}</ref> He was taken to [[Goulburn Base Hospital]] under high security; however, on 27 January 2009 Milat was returned to prison after doctors decided surgery was not possible.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/news/milat-lops-finger-back-in-jail/story-fna7dq6e-1111118675241|title=Serial killer Ivan Milat cuts off finger in High Court protest|date=27 January 2009|newspaper=[[News.com.au]]|accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref> Milat had previously self-harmed in 2001, when he swallowed razor blades, staples and other metal objects.<ref name=\"finger\" /> In May 2011, Milat went on a 9-day hunger strike, losing 25 kilograms in an unsuccessful attempt to be given a [[PlayStation]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Bashan|first=Yoni|url=http://www.news.com.au/national/ivan-milat-on-hunger-strike-over-playstation/story-e6frfkvr-1226056097963|title=Ivan Milat on hunger strike over Playstation|date=15 May 2011|work=News.com.au|accessdate=17 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Milat was transferred to the [[Prince of Wales Hospital (Sydney)|Prince of Wales Hospital]], {{NSWcity|Randwick}}, and was subsequently diagnosed with terminal [[oesophageal cancer]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/serial-killer-ivan-milat-unlikely-to-return-to-supermax-after-terminal-cancer-diagnosis-20190516-p51nu5.html|title=Serial killer Ivan Milat unlikely to return to supermax after terminal cancer diagnosis|last=Cormack|first=Lucy|date=15 May 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=16 May 2019}}</ref> Following his treatment he was transferred to the [[Long Bay Correctional Centre]] to continue his custodial sentences.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/ivan-milat-moves-to-long-bay-jail-hospital-from-prince-of-wales-20190521-p51pjl.html|title=Ivan Milat moves to Long Bay jail hospital from Prince of Wales|date=28 May 2019|access-date=5 Jul 2019}}</ref> On 9 August 2019, a terminally ill Milat was moved to a secure treatment unit located at the [[Prince of Wales Hospital (Sydney)|Prince of Wales Hospital]] following the loss of 20 kilograms in previous weeks; Milat was also exhibiting a high temperature. His status, however, was reported as not life-threatening.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Serial killer Ivan Milat transferred to Sydney hospital from jail|url=https://www.news.com.au/national/nsw-act/news/serial-killer-ivan-milat-transferred-to-sydney-hospital-from-jail/news-story/aacc98d5c80e09ff74e064377939960b|accessdate=9 August 2019|work=[[The 7.30 Report]]|date=9 August 2019}}</ref> On 27 October 2019, Milat died from oesophagus and stomach cancer at 4:07&nbsp;a.m. within the hospital wing at Long Bay Correctional Centre. He was 74 years old.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/rot-in-hell-australia-s-most-notorious-serial-killer-ivan-milat-74-dies|title='Rot in hell': Australia\u2019s most notorious serial killer Ivan Milat, 74, dies|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\nPrior to his death, Milat wrote a letter to his family requesting that his funeral be paid for by the New South Wales Government. The request was denied by NSW Corrections Minister Anthony Roberts. Instead, Milat's body was cremated with the full reimbursement of costs to be paid from his prison account.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-10/ivan-milat-forced-to-pay-for-his-own-cremation/11690598|title=Ivan Milat's dying request refused|date=2019-11-10|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\n== Other developments ==\nOn 8 November 2004, Milat gave a televised interview on ''[[Australian Story]]'', in which he denied that any of his family had been implicated in the seven murders.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stewart|first1=John|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2004-11-08/milat-says-brothers-innocent/581290|title=Milat says brothers innocent|date=8 November 2004|work=ABC News|accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref> A miniseries on the [[Seven Network]], ''[[Catching Milat]]'', screened in 2015 and focused on the members of \"Task Force Air\" who tracked Milat.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Blundell|first1=Graeme|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/review/catching-milat-revisits-backpacker-murders/news-story/bf63c8648451fb0bf2f8118fcd2db555|title=Catching Milat revisits backpacker murders|date=16 May 2005|work=The Australian|accessdate=9 January 2017}}</ref> A book by Milat's nephew, Alistair Shipsey, ''The Milat Letters'' ({{ISBN|1785547844}}) was released in 2016;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Milat-Letters-Alistair-Shipsey/dp/1785547844|title=The Milat Letters|website=www.amazon.com|access-date=2019-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Murray|first=David|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/serial-killer-milat-in-advance-stages-of-cancer/news-story/af9201d3736940d9085e55f1184e9caa|title=Serial killer Milat \u2018has little chance of survival\u2019|date=16 May 2019|work=The Australian|access-date=16 May 2019|last2=Cortis}}</ref> In December 2018, Australian author [[Amanda Howard]] was writing a book on his crimes, based on her correspondence with Milat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/ivan-milat-letters-20190517-p51ok3.html|title='He\u2019s very confident of going to heaven': the letters of Ivan Milat|last=Begley|first=Lucy Cormack, Patrick|date=2019-05-18|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Milat's great-nephew Matthew Milat and his friend Cohen Klein (both aged 19 at the time of their sentencing) were sentenced to 43 years and 32 years in prison, respectively, for murdering David Auchterlonie on his 17th birthday with an axe at the Belanglo State Forest in November 2010. Matthew Milat struck Auchterlonie with the double-headed axe as Klein audio-recorded the attack with a mobile phone.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wells|first=Jamelle|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-06-08/milat-relative-gets-30-years-for-axe-murder/4060442|title=Milat relative gets 30 years for axe murder|date=9 June 2012|newspaper=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dale|first=Amy|url=http://www.news.com.au/national/matthew-milat-sentenced-to-43-years/story-e6frfkvr-1226388884080|title=Matthew Milat sentenced to 30 years jail for 'cold blooded' murder|date=8 June 2012|newspaper=News.com.au|accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, Milat's brother Boris Milat told Steve Aperen, a former homicide detective who serves as a consultant with the [[Los Angeles Police Department]] and the U.S. [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]], that Milat was responsible for another shooting: that of taxi cab driver Neville Knight, in 1962 after Milat admitted to the crime. After conducting [[polygraph]] tests with Boris Milat and Allan Dillon, the man convicted of Knight's shooting, Aperen is convinced that Milat did in fact shoot Knight.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lees|first1=Philippa|url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/sunday-night/features/a/27411151/detective-says-no-doubt-over-ivan-milat-claim/|title=Detective Says 'No Doubt' Over Ivan Milat Claim|date=3 May 2015|work=[[Yahoo! News]]|accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1975, Milat met a 16-year-old girl who was pregnant by his cousin.<ref name=\":2\" /> They married in 1983, making him stepfather to her son, and they had one daughter of their own.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=DTWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dailytelegraph.com.au%2Fnews%2Fnsw%2Fivan-milats-daughter-lynise-opens-up-on-serial-killers-death%2Fnews-story%2F3e70be6273440c17f89ac809b02136cb&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=15c89cd59c57698848bd5786d8066292-1582844345|title=Dailytelegraph.com.au {{!}} Subscribe to The Daily Telegraph for exclusive stories|website=www.dailytelegraph.com.au|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Kennedy|first=Les|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=acfCYGPaqCoC&pg=PT152&lpg=PT152&dq=karen+duck+jason+milat&source=bl&ots=FDTaZo9dpu&sig=ACfU3U2406H5mncOA-kQq5tMqGwYpd4AiQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwibxOnFgMflAhULXn0KHcz3D8IQ6AEwFXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=karen%20duck%20jason%20milat&f=false|title=Sins of the Brother|last2=Whittaker|first2=Mark|date=2007-11-10|publisher=Pan Macmillan Australia|isbn=978-1-74262-404-4|language=en}}</ref> However, she left him in 1987 due to [[domestic violence]] and they divorced in October 1989.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Milat, Ivan}}\n[[Category:Australian people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Croatian descent]]\n[[Category:Australian prisoners sentenced to multiple life sentences]]\n[[Category:Australian rapists]]\n[[Category:Australian serial killers]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Male serial killers]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by New South Wales]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian criminals]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Convicted murderer (b. 1944, d. 2019)}}{{Lead too short|date=February 2020}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox serial killer\n| name = \n| image = Ivan Milat.jpg\n| caption = Milat's 1971 [[mug shot]]\n| birth_name = Ivan Robert Marko Milat\n| signature = Ivan_milat_signature.png\n| alias = \"Bill\"<br>The Backpacker Killer<br>The Backpacker Murderer\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1944|12|27|}}\n| birth_place = {{NSWcity|Guildford}}, [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2019|10|27|1944|12|27|}}\n| death_place = [[Long Bay Correctional Centre]]<br/>[[Matraville, New South Wales]], Australia\n| nationality = Australian\n| known_for = [[Backpacker murders]]\n| victims = 7\n| weapons = [[.22 LR|.22 calibre]] [[Ruger 10/22]]<br>\n[[Bowie knife]]\n| country = Australian\n| states = [[New South Wales]]\n| employer = [[Roads & Traffic Authority]]\n| beginyear = 1989\n| endyear = 1993\n| apprehended = 22 May 1994\n| conviction = 7 counts [[murder]] (27 July 1996)<br>\n1 count [[attempted murder]] (27 July 1996)<br>\n1 count [[false imprisonment]] (27 July 1996)<br>\n1 count [[robbery]] (27 July 1996)\n| sentence = 7 [[life sentences]] without parole ([[murder]])<br>\n6 years imprisonment ([[attempted murder]])<br>\n6 years imprisonment ([[false imprisonment]])<br>\n6 years imprisonment ([[robbery]])\n| conviction_status = Deceased\n| imprisoned = [[Long Bay Correctional Centre]] (2019-d)<br>\n[[Goulburn Correctional Centre]] (1997-2019)<br>\n[[Maitland Gaol]] (1996-1997)\n}}\n'''Ivan Robert Marko Milat''' (27 December 1944 \u2013 27 October 2019<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Malcolm|last2=Feneley|first2=Rick|title=Life never a picnic for the dirt-poor, troubled Milat clan|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/life-never-a-picnic-for-the-dirtpoor-troubled-milat-clan-20101123-185r8.html|accessdate=1 April 2017|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=24 November 2010}}</ref>) was an Australian serial killer who was convicted of the [[backpacker murders]] in 1996.\n\n==Early life==\nIvan Milat was the son of a [[Croats|Croatian]] emigrant and labourer, Stjepan Marko \"Steven\" Milat (1902\u20131983), and an Australian, Margaret Elizabeth Piddleston (1920\u20132001), who married when she was 16.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Malcolm|last2=Feneley|first2=Rick|title=Life never a picnic for the dirt-poor, troubled Milat clan|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/life-never-a-picnic-for-the-dirtpoor-troubled-milat-clan-20101123-185r8.html|accessdate=26 January 2018|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=24 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kennedy|first1=Les|title=Does crime run in the Milat family tree?|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/does-crime-run-in-the-milat-family-tree-20101127-18bg2.html|accessdate=25 January 2018|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=28 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heavenaddress.com/restingplace/margaret-elizabeth-milat/278434|title=Margaret Elizabeth Milat \u2013 HeavenAddress Resting Place|website=www.heavenaddress.com|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref> Milat was the fifth-born of their 14 children,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|last1=Kennedy|first1=Les|title=Milat case stalked by uncertainty|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/stalked-by-uncertainty/2005/07/20/1121539033488.html|accessdate=25 January 2018|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=21 July 2005}}</ref> and the growing family first lived in [[Bossley Park]] before relocating to [[Liverpool, New South Wales|Liverpool]]. Many of the 10 Milat boys were well known to local police, and Milat displayed antisocial behaviour at a young age, leading to a stint in a residential school at age 13.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://casefilepodcast.com/case-109-belanglo-part-3/|title=Case 109: Belanglo (Part 3)|date=6 April 2019|publisher=}}</ref> By 17, he was in a juvenile detention centre for theft, and at 19, was involved in a shop break in.<ref name=\":2\" /> In 1964, he was sentenced to 18 months for a break and enter, and a month after release, he was arrested for driving a stolen car and was sentenced to 2 years hard labour.<ref name=\":2\" /> In September 1967, aged 23, he was sentenced to 3 years for theft.<ref name=\":2\" /> In April 1971, he was charged with the abduction of two 18 year-old hitchhikers and the rape of one of them.<ref name=\"Bio\">{{cite web|title=Ivan Milat Biography|url=http://www.biography.com/people/ivan-milat-17169710|work=[[The Biography Channel]]|publisher=A+E Television Networks, LLC.|accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref> While awaiting trial, he was involved in a string of robberies with some of his brothers, before faking his suicide and fleeing to New Zealand for a year.<ref name=\":2\" /> He was rearrested in 1974, but the robbery and kidnap cases against him failed at trial with the help of the Milat's family lawyer, [[John Marsden (lawyer)|John Marsden]]. He took on a job as a truck driver in 1975, and by the time of the [[Belanglo State Forest]] crimes, Milat had worked on and off for 20 years for the [[Roads & Traffic Authority]] all over the state.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Backpacker murders==\n{{main|Backpacker murders}}\n\n===Background===\nBy the time of the first Belanglo State Forest discoveries, several backpackers had been reported missing. One case involved a young [[Victoria (Australia)|Victorian]] couple from [[Frankston, Victoria|Frankston]], Deborah Everist (19) and James Gibson (19), who had been missing since leaving Sydney for [[ConFest]], near Albury, on 30 December 1989.<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://casefilepodcast.com/case-109-belanglo-part-1/|title=Case 109: Belanglo (Part 1)|date=2019-03-23|website=Casefile: True Crime Podcast|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-31}}</ref> Another related to Simone Schmidl (21), from Germany, who had been missing since leaving Sydney for Melbourne on 20 January 1991.<ref name=\":32\" /> Similarly, a German couple, Gabor Neugebauer (21) and Anja Habschied (20), had disappeared after leaving a [[Kings Cross, New South Wales|Kings Cross]] hostel for Mildura on 26 December 1991. Another involved missing British backpackers Caroline Clarke (21) and Joanne Walters (22), who were last seen in Kings Cross on 18 April 1992.<ref name=\"Sorrow\">{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/friends-born-of-sorrow/2006/04/23/1145730809381.html'?page=fullpage|title=Friends born of sorrow|last=Meacham|first=Steve|date=24 April 2006|newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Discovery of victims ===\n[[File:Belanglo_State_Forest_sign.jpg|right|thumb|A sign at the entrance to the Belanglo State Forest]]\nOn 19 September 1992, two runners discovered a concealed corpse while [[orienteering]] in Belanglo.<ref name=\"25yearsago2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/twenty-five-years-ago-the-first-victims-of-backpacker-killer-ivan-milat-were-found-in-belanglo-forest-twenty-five-years-ago-the-first-victims-of-backpacker-killer-ivan-milat-were-found-in-belanglo-forest/news-story/f4a31abad223faa68d8d73ca054d297e|title=Twenty five years ago the first victims of Backpacker Killer Ivan Milat were found in Belanglo Forest|last1=Lennon|first1=Troy|date=19 September 2017|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]}}</ref> The following morning, police discovered a second body {{convert|30|m|ft}} from the first.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=acfCYGPaqCoC&pg=PT322|title=Sins of the Brother: The Definitive Story of Ivan Milat and the Backpacker Murders|last1=Whittaker|first1=Mark|last2=Kennedy|first2=Les|date=10 November 2007|publisher=Pan Macmillan Australia|isbn=978-0-330-36284-9|pages=267\u2013268, 322|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref> Police quickly confirmed, via dental records, that the bodies were those of Clarke and Walters.<ref name=\":32\" /> A search of the area failed to uncover any of the other missing backpackers.\n\nIn October 1993, however, a local man searching for firewood discovered bones in a particularly remote section of the forest.<ref name=\"Brown20002\">{{cite book|title=Bombs, Guns and Knives: Violent Crime in Australia|last=Brown|first=Malcolm|publisher=New Holland|year=2000|isbn=1-86436-668-0|location=Sydney|pages=148\u2013153}}</ref> He returned with police to the scene where two bodies were quickly discovered and later identified as Gibson and Everist. The presence of Gibson's body in Belanglo puzzled investigators as his camera and backpack had previously been discovered at [[Galston Gorge]], over {{convert|120|km}} to the north.<ref name=\"Sorrow\" /><ref name=\":32\" />\n\nOn 1 November 1993, a skeleton was found in a clearing along a fire trail in the forest during a police sweep.<ref name=\"Timeline2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.crimeandinvestigation.co.uk/crime-files/ivan-milat/timeline.html|title=Timeline|work=[[Crime & Investigation Network]]|publisher=AETN UK|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref> It was later identified as that of Schmidl.<ref name=\"Sorrow\" /> Clothing found at the scene was not Schmidl's, but matched that of another missing backpacker, Habschied.<ref name=\":32\" /> On 4 November 1993, the bodies of Habschied and Neugebauer were then found on a nearby fire trail in shallow graves {{convert|50|m}} apart.<ref name=\"Nine\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/archive/news/the-nine-bodies-found-in-belanglo-forest/story-e6frg6o6-1225958668442|title=The nine bodies found in Belanglo forest|date=22 November 2010|newspaper=[[The Australian]]|accessdate=13 January 2014|agency=[[Australian Associated Press|AAP]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Search for a serial killer ===\nExamination of the remains showed evidence that some of the victims had been tortured and did not die instantly from their injuries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-48346543|title=The 'backpacker killer' and unanswered questions|last=Nunn|first=Gary|date=27 October 2019|via=www.bbc.com|accessdate=27 October 2019}}</ref> In response, on 14 October 1993, Task Force Air, containing more than 20 detectives and analysts, was set up by the [[New South Wales Police Force|NSW Police]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://casefilepodcast.com/case-109-belanglo-part-2/|title=Case 109: Belanglo (Part 2) cebo|date=30 March 2019|website=Casefile: True Crime Podcast}}</ref> On 5 November 1993, the NSW government increased the reward in relation to the killings to $500,000.<ref name=\":1\" /> After developing their [[Offender profiling|profile]] of the killer, the police faced an enormous volume of data from numerous sources.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aic.gov.au/media_library/conferences/outlook4/mouzos.pdf|title=Investigating Homicide: New Responses for an Old Crime|last=Mouzos|first=Jenny|work=[[Australian Institute of Criminology]]|publisher=Australian Government|page=5|format=PDF|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref> Investigators applied [[link analysis]] technology, and as a result, the list of suspects was narrowed from a short list of 230 to an even shorter list of 32.<ref>{{cite book|title=Machine Learning Forensics for Law Enforcement, Security, and Intelligence|last=Mena|first=Jes\u00fas|publisher=CRC Press (Taylor & Francis Group)|year=2011|isbn=978-1-4398-6069-4|location=Boca Raton, FL}}</ref> Speculation arose that the crimes were the work of several killers,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dDOW75aJMR8C&pg=PA313|title=Encyclopedia of Murder and Violent Crime|last=Hickey|first=Eric W.|date=22 July 2003|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-0-7619-2437-1|page=313|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/australasia/did-australias-backpacker-killer-have-an-accomplice-2198469.html|title=Did Australia's backpacker killer have an accomplice?|last=Maynard|first=Roger|date=30 January 2011|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref> given that most of the victims had been attacked while as pairs, had been killed in different ways, and buried separately.\n\nOn 13 November 1993, police received a call from Paul Onions (24) in the U.K. On 25 January 1990, Onions had been backpacking in Australia and, while hitchhiking from [[Liverpool railway station, Sydney|Liverpool station]] towards [[Mildura]], had accepted a ride south out of [[Casula, New South Wales|Casula]] from a man known only as \"Bill\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/belanglo-state-forest-once-again-the-home-of-nightmarish-murder/news-story/16f26fd7b5a8d83d658b15059a780435|title=Belanglo State Forest once again the home of nightmarish murder|last1=Starick|first1=Paul|date=22 October 2015|work=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]|accessdate=26 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Newton20062\">{{cite book|last=Newton|first=Michael|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DwNVbOcTncwC&pg=PA178|title=The Encyclopedia of Serial Killers|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-0-8160-6987-3|pages=178\u2013179|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref> South of the town of [[Mittagong]], and less than 1&nbsp;km from Belanglo State Forest, Bill stopped and pulled out a revolver and some ropes stating it was a robbery, at which point Onions managed to flee.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/law-order/true-crime-scene/backpacker-murders-how-backpacker-paul-onions-survived-a-close-encounter-with-evil-ivan-milat/news-story/440554edab618a9bcf8ea0de17c3a21b|title=Backpacker murders: How backpacker Paul Onions survived a close encounter with evil Ivan Milat|date=15 May 2015|work=Herald Sun|accessdate=26 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/tv-reviews/born-to-kill--ivan-milat/2006/07/25/1153746844314.html|title=Born to Kill \u2013 Ivan Milat|last=Oliver|first=Robin|date=26 July 2006|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=11 January 2014}}</ref> Onions flagged down a passing motorist, and together they described the assailant and his vehicle to the [[Bowral]] police.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/national/backpacker-who-escaped-ivan-milat-to-return-to-australia/story-e6freooo-1225825004932|title=Backpacker who escaped Ivan Milat to return to Australia|last=Murray|first=David|date=31 January 2010|newspaper=[[The Courier-Mail]]|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref> On 13 April 1994, detectives re-found the note regarding Onions' call. Onions' statement was corroborated by Berry, along with the girlfriend of a man who worked with Milat.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/on-the-trail-of-a--serial-killer-20140413-36m7u.html|title=On the trail of a ... serial killer|last1=Small|first1=Clive|date=19 April 2014|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=26 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Arrest and trial===\nOn 26 February 1994, police surveillance of the Milat house at Cinnabar Street, {{NSWcity|Eagle Vale}} commenced.<ref name=\":2\" /> Police learnt that Milat had recently sold his silver [[Nissan Patrol]] four-wheel drive shortly after the discovery of the bodies of Clarke and Walters.<ref>{{cite book|last=Marriott|first=Trevor|title=The Evil Within \u2013 A Top Murder Squad Detective Reveals The Chilling True Stories of The World's Most Notorious Killers|url=https://archive.org/details/evilwithintopmur0000marr|url-access=registration|accessdate=10 January 2014|date=4 September 2013|publisher=John Blake Publishing|isbn=978-1-78219-365-4|page=[https://archive.org/details/evilwithintopmur0000marr/page/21 21]}}</ref> Police also confirmed that Milat had not been working on any of the days of the attacks<ref name=\":3\" /> and acquaintances also told police about Milat's obsession with weapons.<ref name=\"25yearsago\">{{cite news|last1=Lennon|first1=Troy|title=Twenty five years ago the first victims of Backpacker Killer Ivan Milat were found in Belanglo Forest|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/twenty-five-years-ago-the-first-victims-of-backpacker-killer-ivan-milat-were-found-in-belanglo-forest-twenty-five-years-ago-the-first-victims-of-backpacker-killer-ivan-milat-were-found-in-belanglo-forest/news-story/f4a31abad223faa68d8d73ca054d297e|accessdate=26 January 2018|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=19 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Chapman|first=Simon|title=Over Our Dead Bodies: Port Arthur and Australia's Fight for Gun Control|url=http://ses.library.usyd.edu.au/bitstream/2123/8938/1/Over-our-dead-bodies_Chapman.pdf|accessdate=10 January 2014|year=2013|publisher=Sydney University Press|isbn=978-1-74332-031-0|page=163}}</ref> When the connection between the Belanglo murders and Onions' experience was made, Onions flew to Australia to help with the investigation.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Small|first1=Clive|title=On the trail of a ... serial killer|url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/on-the-trail-of-a--serial-killer-20140413-36m7u.html|accessdate=26 January 2018|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=19 April 2014}}</ref> On 5 May 1994, Onions positively identified Milat as the man who had picked him up and attempted to assault him.<ref name=\"Brown2000\">{{cite book|last=Brown|first=Malcolm|title=Bombs, Guns and Knives: Violent Crime in Australia|year=2000|publisher=New Holland|location=Sydney|isbn=1-86436-668-0|pages=148\u2013153}}</ref>\n\nMilat was arrested at his home on 22 May 1994 on robbery and weapon charges related to the Onions attack after 50 police officers surrounded the house.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/serial_killers/predators/milat/discovery_1.html |title=Ivan Milat: The Last Ride|last=Bellamy |first=Patrick|work=[[TruTV]]|publisher=Time Warner Inc.|pages=12\u201313|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110091143/http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/serial_killers/predators/milat/discovery_1.html|archivedate=10 January 2014 |url-status=dead|accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Timeline\">{{cite web|title=Timeline|url=http://www.crimeandinvestigation.co.uk/crime-files/ivan-milat/timeline.html|work=[[Crime & Investigation Network]]|publisher=AETN UK|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref> The search of Milat's home revealed various weapons, including a [[.22 LR|.22-calibre]] [[J. G. Ansch\u00fctz|Ansch\u00fctz Model 1441/42]] rifle and parts of a .22 calibre [[Ruger 10/22]] rifle that matched the type used in the murders, a [[Browning Arms Company|Browning pistol]], and a [[Bowie knife]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://casefilepodcast.com/case-109-belanglo-part-4/|title=Case 109: Belanglo (Part 4)|date=2019-04-13|website=Casefile: True Crime Podcast|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> Also uncovered were items belonging to several of his victims.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Ivan Milat |url=http://www.citv.com.au/crime-profiles/44/ivan-milat/3/the-crime |work=Crime & Investigation Network |publisher=Foxtel |accessdate=10 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110092804/http://www.citv.com.au/crime-profiles/44/ivan-milat/3/the-crime |archivedate=10 January 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> Homes belonging to his mother and five of his brothers were also searched,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nVJD6V0XAtwC&pg=PT344|title=Australia's Serial Killers|last=Kidd|first=Paul B.|date=1 August 2011|publisher=Pan Macmillan Australia|isbn=978-1-74262-798-4|page=344|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref> uncovering several more items belonging to the victims.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nMilat appeared in court on 23 May, but he did not enter a [[plea]].<ref name=\"Dispatch\">{{cite news|last=Spielman|first=Peter James|title=Suspect charged in seven murders|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1734&dat=19940531&id=MOAhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=1VIEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6928,2645168|accessdate=13 January 2014|newspaper=[[The Dispatch (Lexington)|The Dispatch]]|date=31 May 1994|agency=[[Associated Press|AP]]}}</ref> On 31 May, Milat was also charged with the seven backpacker murders.<ref name=\":4\" /> On 28 June, Milat sacked his defence lawyer, Marsden, and sought legal aid to pay for his defence.<ref name=\":4\" /> Meanwhile, brothers Richard and Walter were tried in relation to weapons, drugs and stolen items found on their properties.<ref name=\":4\" /> A [[Committal procedure|committal hearing]] for Milat regarding the murders began on 24 October and lasted until 12 December, during which over 200 witnesses appeared.<ref name=\":4\" /> Based on the evidence, at the beginning of February 1995, Milat was remanded in custody until June that same year.\n\nOn 26 March 1996, the trial opened at the [[Supreme Court of New South Wales]] and was prosecuted by [[Mark Tedeschi]].<ref name=\"Trial\">{{cite web|title=The Trial|url=http://www.crimeandinvestigation.co.uk/crime-files/ivan-milat/trial.html|work=Crime & Investigation Network|publisher=AETN UK|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref> His defence argued that, in spite of the evidence, there was no non-circumstantial proof Milat was guilty and attempted to shift the blame to other members of his family, particularly Richard.<ref name=\"Trial\" /> 145 witnesses took the stand, including members of the Milat family who endeavoured to provide alibis, and, on 18 June, Milat himself.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://casefilepodcast.com/case-109-belanglo-part-5/|title=Case 109: Belanglo (Part 5)|date=2019-04-20|website=Casefile: True Crime Podcast|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> On 27 July 1996, after 18 weeks of testimony, a jury found Milat guilty of the murders.<ref name=\"Timeline\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Walker|first=Frank|title=Milat's brother claims police still treating him as murder suspect|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/05/22/1085176039666.html?from=storylhs|accessdate=11 January 2014|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=23 May 2004}}</ref> He was given a [[life imprisonment|life sentence]] on each count without the possibility of parole. He was also convicted of the attempted murder, false imprisonment and robbery of Onions, for which he received six years [[jail]] each.<ref name=\"Newton2006\">{{cite book|last=Newton|first=Michael|title=The Encyclopedia of Serial Killers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DwNVbOcTncwC&pg=PA178|accessdate=13 January 2014|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-0-8160-6987-3|pages=178\u2013179}}</ref>\n\n== Incarceration and appeals ==\nOn his first day, when arriving at [[Maitland Gaol]], Milat was beaten by another inmate.<ref>{{cite news|title=Skeleton key to unlock Ivan Milat mystery?|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/skeleton-key-to-unlock-ivan-milat-mystery/story-e6frf7jo-1225912001007|accessdate=10 January 2014|newspaper=[[Herald Sun]]|date=30 August 2010|agency=AAP}}</ref> Almost a year later, on 16 May 1997, he made an escape attempt alongside convicted drug dealer and former Sydney councillor George Savvas.<ref>{{cite news|title=Maitland Correctional Centre Escape Attempt |url=http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/parlment/hansart.nsf/V3Key/LA19970520013 |accessdate=10 January 2014 |newspaper=[[Parliament of New South Wales]] |date=20 May 1997 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110094731/http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/parlment/hansart.nsf/V3Key/LA19970520013 |archivedate=10 January 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> The plan failed and Savvas was found hanged in his cell the next day, and Milat was transferred to the maximum security section at [[Goulburn Correctional Centre]] in [[Goulburn, New South Wales]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Skeleton key to unlock Ivan Milat mystery?|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/skeleton-key-to-unlock-ivan-milat-mystery/news-story/bb675c84c1205e881219048b5b479bf7|accessdate=25 January 2018|work=Herald Sun|agency=AAP|date=30 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn November 1997, Milat appealed against his convictions due to a breach of his common law right to legal representation, as established in ''[[Dietrich v The Queen]]''. However, the [[New South Wales Court of Criminal Appeal]] dismissed the appeal.<ref name=\"Case\">{{cite AustLII|NSWSC|795|1998|litigants=Regina v Milat |date=26 February 1998}}.</ref> In 2004, Milat filed an application with the [[High Court of Australia]] that he be allowed special leave to appeal on new grounds. The application for leave was ultimately dismissed, affirming the Court of Criminal Appeal's decision to disallow his initial appeal.<ref>{{Cite AustLII|HCA|17|2004|litigants=Milat v The Queen |parallelcite=(2004) 205 [[Australian Law Reports|ALR]] 338; (2004) 78 [[Australian Law Journal Reports|ALJR]] |date=24 February 2004}}.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/05/28/1085641690085.html|title=Serial killer Milat loses conviction appeal|agency=AAP|date=28 May 2004|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=20 May 2017}}</ref> On 27 October 2005, in the NSW Supreme Court<ref>{{Cite AustLII|NSWSC|920|2005|litigants=R v Milat (backpacker murders)|date=27 October 2005}}.</ref> Milat's final avenue of appeal was refused.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/4415216.stm|title=Serial killer's appeal is refused|date=7 November 2005|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref> In 2006, two other application attempts were rejected as well, as was one in November 2011.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nIn 2001, following the opening of the High Risk Management Corrections Centre (Supermax) at Goulburn Correctional Centre, Milat was transferred from the maximum security section of the prison into one of its 45 new units.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Australia\u2019s worst serial killer Ivan Milat has died aged 74|url=https://www.news.com.au/national/australias-worst-serial-killer-ivan-milat-has-died-aged-74/news-story/c0ec9be649b146fc3919ce05387b475d|accessdate=29 October 2019|work=[[News.com.au]]|date=27 October 2019}}</ref> In 2006, a toaster and TV given to Milat in his cell caused a public outcry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/milat-gets-tv-toaster-returned-to-cell-20060715-gdnyv3.html|title=Milat gets TV, toaster returned to cell|date=2006-07-14|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Health and death ==\nOn 26 January 2009, Milat cut off his little finger with a plastic knife, with the intention of mailing it to the [[High Court of Australia]] to force an appeal.<ref name=\"finger\">{{cite news|url=http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-national/medics-unable-to-reattach-milats-finger-20090127-7qg5.html|title=Medics unable to reattach Milat's finger|date=27 January 2009|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=27 January 2009|agency=AAP}}</ref> He was taken to [[Goulburn Base Hospital]] under high security; however, on 27 January 2009 Milat was returned to prison after doctors decided surgery was not possible.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/news/milat-lops-finger-back-in-jail/story-fna7dq6e-1111118675241|title=Serial killer Ivan Milat cuts off finger in High Court protest|date=27 January 2009|newspaper=[[News.com.au]]|accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref> Milat had previously self-harmed in 2001, when he swallowed razor blades, staples and other metal objects.<ref name=\"finger\" /> In May 2011, Milat went on a 9-day hunger strike, losing 25 kilograms in an unsuccessful attempt to be given a [[PlayStation]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Bashan|first=Yoni|url=http://www.news.com.au/national/ivan-milat-on-hunger-strike-over-playstation/story-e6frfkvr-1226056097963|title=Ivan Milat on hunger strike over Playstation|date=15 May 2011|work=News.com.au|accessdate=17 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Milat was transferred to the [[Prince of Wales Hospital (Sydney)|Prince of Wales Hospital]], {{NSWcity|Randwick}}, and was subsequently diagnosed with terminal [[oesophageal cancer]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/serial-killer-ivan-milat-unlikely-to-return-to-supermax-after-terminal-cancer-diagnosis-20190516-p51nu5.html|title=Serial killer Ivan Milat unlikely to return to supermax after terminal cancer diagnosis|last=Cormack|first=Lucy|date=15 May 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=16 May 2019}}</ref> Following his treatment he was transferred to the [[Long Bay Correctional Centre]] to continue his custodial sentences.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/ivan-milat-moves-to-long-bay-jail-hospital-from-prince-of-wales-20190521-p51pjl.html|title=Ivan Milat moves to Long Bay jail hospital from Prince of Wales|date=28 May 2019|access-date=5 Jul 2019}}</ref> On 9 August 2019, a terminally ill Milat was moved to a secure treatment unit located at the [[Prince of Wales Hospital (Sydney)|Prince of Wales Hospital]] following the loss of 20 kilograms in previous weeks; Milat was also exhibiting a high temperature. His status, however, was reported as not life-threatening.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Serial killer Ivan Milat transferred to Sydney hospital from jail|url=https://www.news.com.au/national/nsw-act/news/serial-killer-ivan-milat-transferred-to-sydney-hospital-from-jail/news-story/aacc98d5c80e09ff74e064377939960b|accessdate=9 August 2019|work=[[The 7.30 Report]]|date=9 August 2019}}</ref> On 27 October 2019, Milat died from oesophagus and stomach cancer at 4:07&nbsp;a.m. within the hospital wing at Long Bay Correctional Centre. He was 74 years old.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/rot-in-hell-australia-s-most-notorious-serial-killer-ivan-milat-74-dies|title='Rot in hell': Australia\u2019s most notorious serial killer Ivan Milat, 74, dies|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\nPrior to his death, Milat wrote a letter to his family requesting that his funeral be paid for by the New South Wales Government. The request was denied by NSW Corrections Minister Anthony Roberts. Instead, Milat's body was cremated with the full reimbursement of costs to be paid from his prison account.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-10/ivan-milat-forced-to-pay-for-his-own-cremation/11690598|title=Ivan Milat's dying request refused|date=2019-11-10|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\n== Other developments ==\nOn 8 November 2004, Milat gave a televised interview on ''[[Australian Story]]'', in which he denied that any of his family had been implicated in the seven murders.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stewart|first1=John|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2004-11-08/milat-says-brothers-innocent/581290|title=Milat says brothers innocent|date=8 November 2004|work=ABC News|accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref> A miniseries on the [[Seven Network]], ''[[Catching Milat]]'', screened in 2015 and focused on the members of \"Task Force Air\" who tracked Milat.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Blundell|first1=Graeme|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/review/catching-milat-revisits-backpacker-murders/news-story/bf63c8648451fb0bf2f8118fcd2db555|title=Catching Milat revisits backpacker murders|date=16 May 2005|work=The Australian|accessdate=9 January 2017}}</ref> A book by Milat's nephew, Alistair Shipsey, ''The Milat Letters'' ({{ISBN|1785547844}}) was released in 2016;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Milat-Letters-Alistair-Shipsey/dp/1785547844|title=The Milat Letters|website=www.amazon.com|access-date=2019-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Murray|first=David|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/serial-killer-milat-in-advance-stages-of-cancer/news-story/af9201d3736940d9085e55f1184e9caa|title=Serial killer Milat \u2018has little chance of survival\u2019|date=16 May 2019|work=The Australian|access-date=16 May 2019|last2=Cortis}}</ref> In December 2018, Australian author [[Amanda Howard]] was writing a book on his crimes, based on her correspondence with Milat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/ivan-milat-letters-20190517-p51ok3.html|title='He\u2019s very confident of going to heaven': the letters of Ivan Milat|last=Begley|first=Lucy Cormack, Patrick|date=2019-05-18|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Milat's great-nephew Matthew Milat and his friend Cohen Klein (both aged 19 at the time of their sentencing) were sentenced to 43 years and 32 years in prison, respectively, for murdering David Auchterlonie on his 17th birthday with an axe at the Belanglo State Forest in November 2010. Matthew Milat struck Auchterlonie with the double-headed axe as Klein audio-recorded the attack with a mobile phone.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wells|first=Jamelle|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-06-08/milat-relative-gets-30-years-for-axe-murder/4060442|title=Milat relative gets 30 years for axe murder|date=9 June 2012|newspaper=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dale|first=Amy|url=http://www.news.com.au/national/matthew-milat-sentenced-to-43-years/story-e6frfkvr-1226388884080|title=Matthew Milat sentenced to 30 years jail for 'cold blooded' murder|date=8 June 2012|newspaper=News.com.au|accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, Milat's brother Boris Milat told Steve Aperen, a former homicide detective who serves as a consultant with the [[Los Angeles Police Department]] and the U.S. [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]], that Milat was responsible for another shooting: that of taxi cab driver Neville Knight, in 1962 after Milat admitted to the crime. After conducting [[polygraph]] tests with Boris Milat and Allan Dillon, the man convicted of Knight's shooting, Aperen is convinced that Milat did in fact shoot Knight.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lees|first1=Philippa|url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/sunday-night/features/a/27411151/detective-says-no-doubt-over-ivan-milat-claim/|title=Detective Says 'No Doubt' Over Ivan Milat Claim|date=3 May 2015|work=[[Yahoo! News]]|accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1975, Milat met a 16-year-old girl who was pregnant by his cousin.<ref name=\":2\" /> They married in 1983, making him stepfather to her son, and they had one daughter of their own.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=DTWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dailytelegraph.com.au%2Fnews%2Fnsw%2Fivan-milats-daughter-lynise-opens-up-on-serial-killers-death%2Fnews-story%2F3e70be6273440c17f89ac809b02136cb&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=15c89cd59c57698848bd5786d8066292-1582844345|title=Dailytelegraph.com.au {{!}} Subscribe to The Daily Telegraph for exclusive stories|website=www.dailytelegraph.com.au|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Kennedy|first=Les|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=acfCYGPaqCoC&pg=PT152&lpg=PT152&dq=karen+duck+jason+milat&source=bl&ots=FDTaZo9dpu&sig=ACfU3U2406H5mncOA-kQq5tMqGwYpd4AiQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwibxOnFgMflAhULXn0KHcz3D8IQ6AEwFXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=karen%20duck%20jason%20milat&f=false|title=Sins of the Brother|last2=Whittaker|first2=Mark|date=2007-11-10|publisher=Pan Macmillan Australia|isbn=978-1-74262-404-4|language=en}}</ref> However, she left him in 1987 due to [[domestic violence]] and they divorced in October 1989.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Milat, Ivan}}\n[[Category:Australian people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Croatian descent]]\n[[Category:Australian prisoners sentenced to multiple life sentences]]\n[[Category:Australian rapists]]\n[[Category:Australian serial killers]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Male serial killers]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by New South Wales]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian criminals]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "2001:8004:e00:1309:4498:dbe6:e4b4:fcca", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Type)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivan_Milat"}
{"title_page": "Lukas Gage", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{COI|date=December 2017}}\n{{infobox person\n|birth_place  = [[San Diego, California]], U.S.\n|home_town    = [[Encinitas, California]], U.S.\n|occupation   = Actor\n|years_active = 2012\u2013present\n|[[File:Lukas Gage.jpg|thumb|Lukas Gage]]\n}}\n'''Lukas Gage''' is an American actor. He has appeared in ''[[American Vandal]]'', ''[[T@gged]]'', ''[[Scouts Guide to the Zombie Apocalypse]]'' and \n''[[Euphoria (American TV series)|Euphoria]]''.\n\n==Early life and education==\nGage was born in [[San Diego, California]] and raised in [[Encinitas, California]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.10news.com/news/encinitas-actor-lukas-gage-stars-in-netflix-show-set-in-oceanside|title=Encinitas actor Lukas Gage stars in Netflix show set in Oceanside|first=Matt|last=Boone|date=September 18, 2017|website=10news.com|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> As a child he went to film camp every summer<ref name=\"galoremag.com\">{{cite web|url=https://galoremag.com/mcm-lukas-gage-never-been-on-date/|title=#MCM: Lukas Gage Has Never Been On a Real Date Before|author=|date=March 13, 2017|website=galoremag.com|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> and acted in plays and commercials.<ref name=\"sandiegoreader.com\"/> He attended [[San Dieguito Academy]] in Encinitas.<ref name=\"sandiegoreader.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sandiegoreader.com/news/2017/aug/10/stringers-american-vandal-mockumentary-oceanside/|title=American Vandal mockumentary of Oceanside High doesn't ring a bell|author=|date=|website=sandiegoreader.com|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n!Reference\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2014\n|''Animals''\n|Daniel\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Short film\n|<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm4965072/|title=Lukas Gage|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n|-\n|''Satellite Beach''\n|Big Dean\u2019s server\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oxymoronent.com/movies/Satellite_Beach/|title=Satellite Beach Movie|website=Oxymoron Entertainment|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Scouts Guide to the Zombie Apocalypse]]''\n|Travis\n|\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/563be2fb1a93f|title=Lukas Gage - BFI|author=|date=|website=www.bfi.org.uk|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Sickhouse]]''\n|Lukas\n|\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/digital/news/sickhouse-andrea-russett-snapchat-vimeo-1201786822/|title=First Movie Filmed on Snapchat, 'Sickhouse' Starring Andrea Russett, Debuts on Vimeo|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=2016-06-01|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n|-\n|2017\n|''Sleep No More''\n|Carter\n|\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.filmaffinity.com/en/film160291.html|title=200 Hours (2018)|author=|date=|website=filmaffinity.com|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2018\n|''Ace''\n|Ace\n|Short film\n|<ref>{{Citation|title=ACE (Short Film)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=26wvLqisJuw|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Assassination Nation]]''\n|Eric\n|\n|<ref name=\"galoremag.com\" />\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2019\n|''Wyrm''\n|Dylan\n|\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://freshfiction.tv/fantastic-fest-review%e2%80%8b-wyrm-a-coming-of-age-story-with-the-dna-of-taika-waititi-and-wes-anderson/|title=[Fantastic Fest review] 'WYRM' a coming-of-age story with the DNA of Taika Waititi and Wes Anderson|date=2019-09-23|website=FreshFiction.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n|-\n|''Deadcon''\n|Ricky\n|Short film\n|\n|-\n|2020\n|[[The Way Back (2020 film)|''The Way Back'']]\n|Eddie\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Post-production\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.harkins.com/movies/the-way-back-86640-0|title=The Way Back At Harkins Theatres|website=www.harkins.com|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |TBA\n|''What Breaks the Ice''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Seth\n|\n|-\n|''Max Reload and the Nether Blasters''\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Episode\n!Reference\n|-\n|2013\n|[[Enlightened (TV series)|''Enlightened'']]\n|Therapy Group Member\n|Episode: \u201cHigher Power\u201d\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2014\n|[[I Didn't Do It (TV series)|''I Didn't Do It'']]\n|Guy\n|Episode: \u201cBall or Nothing\u201d\n|\n|-\n|[[Kingdom (American TV series)|''Kingdom'']]\n|Skinner\n|Episode: \u201cPiece of Plastic\u201d\n|\n|-\n|2016-2018\n|''[[T@gged]]''\n|Brandon Darrow\n|Main Role\n|<ref name=\"sandiegoreader.com\" />\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |2017\n|''Apologies in Advance with Andrea Russett''\n|Himself\n|Episode: \u201cLukas Gage\u201d\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|[[Confess (TV series)|''Confess'']]\n|Adam Taylor\n|2 episodes\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|''[[Adam Ruins Everything]]''\n|Cole Tyson\n|Episode: \u201cAdam Ruins College\u201d\n|\n|-\n|''[[American Vandal]]''\n|Brandon Galloway\n|5 episodes\n|<ref name=\"auto\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.populartv.com/etc/guy-popular-lukas-gage/|title=Popular TV - The Anti-Social Network|author=|date=|website=www.populartv.com|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|''Give Good Text''\n|Himself\n|2 episodes\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2018\n|[[On My Block (TV series)|''On My Block'']]\n|Brad\n|Episode: \u201cChapter Four\u201d\n|<ref name=\"auto\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvweb.com/on-my-block-trailer-netflix-original-series/|title='On My Block' Trailer Takes Netflix Deep into South Central L.A|date=January 30, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|''Class of Lies''\n|Tiger\n|5 episodes\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2019\n|[[Supergirl (TV series)|''Supergirl'']]\n|Kevin Huggins\n|Episode: \u201cBlood Memory\u201d\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|''[[Veronica Mars]]''\n|Cory\n|Episode: \u201cKeep Calm and Party On\u201d\n|<ref>{{Citation|title=Veronica Mars: Keep Calm and Party On {{!}} TVmaze|url=https://www.tvmaze.com/episodes/1638980/veronica-mars-4x03-keep-calm-and-party-on|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Euphoria (American TV series)|''Euphoria'']]\n|Tyler\n|4 episodes\n|<ref name=\"sandiegoreader.com\" />\n|-\n|[[Into the Dark (TV series)|''Into the Dark'']]\n|TBA\n|Episode: \u201cMidnight Kiss\u201d\n|<ref>Ramos, Dino-Ray (November 8, 2019). \"'Into The Dark': Augustus Prew, Scott Evans, Ayden Mayeri Among 6 Cast In New Year's-Themed 'Midnight Kiss' Installment Of Horror Anthology\". ''Deadline Hollywood''. Retrieved November 14, 2019.</ref>\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Love, Victor]]''\n|Derek\n|\n|<ref>{{Citation|title=Episode #1.1|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt10482214/|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External Links==\n* {{IMDb name|nm4965072}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gage, Lukas}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:People from San Diego, California]]\n[[Category:People from Encinitas, California]]\n[[Category:Male actors from California]]\n\n{{US-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{COI|date=December 2017}}\n{{infobox person\n|birth_place  = [[San Diego, California]], U.S.\n|home_town    = [[Encinitas, California]], U.S.\n|occupation   = Actor\n|years_active = 2012\u2013present\n|date_of_birth = May 28, 1995\n}}\n'''Lukas Gage''' is an American actor. He has appeared in ''[[American Vandal]]'', ''[[T@gged]]'', ''[[Scouts Guide to the Zombie Apocalypse]]'' and \n''[[Euphoria (American TV series)|Euphoria]]''.\n\n==Early life and education==\nGage was born in [[San Diego, California]] and raised in [[Encinitas, California]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.10news.com/news/encinitas-actor-lukas-gage-stars-in-netflix-show-set-in-oceanside|title=Encinitas actor Lukas Gage stars in Ne